residents ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The yellow police tape surrounding the sprawling one-story brick school provided a jarring note on the quiet, tree-lined, sunny street with its comfortable homes. But the tranquility of this affluent <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shore </LOCATION> community had already been shattered by a shooting rampage that left an 8-year-old boy dead and five other children and an adult critically wounded. The children were shot at <ORGANIZATION> Hubbard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in a 15-minute assault by a woman Friday morning in a school restroom and in a second-grade classroom. The woman barricaded herself in a neighboring home and was found dead by police later in the day. Police said she shot herself once in the head with a .32 - caliber School District 36 Superintentent <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON>, his shirt stained with blood, tried to reassure anxious parents who gathered outside, and the crowd dispersed quickly. `` There were a lot of mothers trying to get to the school'' immediately afterward, said a resident of the neighborhood, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Belmont </PERSON>. `` They're all crying on my front lawn,'' said another resident, <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Prange </PERSON>. `` These things happen 2,000 miles away. They do n't happen next door to you,'' said a third resident, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosler </PERSON>. After the classroom shooting, the drama shifted to the nearby home, where a young man was shot and the suspect, identified as 30-year-old <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Dann </PERSON>, barricaded herself inside. `` I just heard police surrounding the house, calling, ` <PERSON> Lori </PERSON>, let's get it over with.' I did n't hear any response. Then I heard a shot, a blast I would say,'' said <PERSON> Hildegard </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberstoetter </PERSON>, a housekeeper at the home next door. The afternoon dragged into evening. Reporters were kept behind a police line. Trees obscured the houses. Dozens of police officers waited in the street, and squad cars came and went. After eight hours, <ORGANIZATION> Winnetka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Timm </PERSON> announced Ms. <PERSON> Dann </PERSON> had been found dead in the house. Village residents talked of little else. Teen-agers sitting on cars in a local gas station were discussing the events, and a man sat in his garage listening to developments on a police radio. The boy's death was only the third slaying in his community since 1957, <PERSON> Timm </PERSON> said. `` We never have a drill for something like this. But we do have fire and tornado drills, so the kids were on the floor in the other classrooms'' after the shooting, <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> said. Standing outside the school at the end of the day, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Romey </PERSON> said his 7-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Katie </PERSON>, was in another classroom when the shooting occurred. `` I'm relieved to hear our child is safe. It's a tragedy. It's just terrible for the family who lost their child,'' he said `` The kids are calm,'' said his wife, <PERSON> Blanche </PERSON>, adding that school officials `` told us to take them home and let them talk because they've been talked to a lot today.'' `` The school system here is known for being fantastic, and they have handled this whole thing fantastically,'' Ms. <PERSON> Romey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> `` is a fabulous school _ one of the best in the country. ... It's a family neighborhood,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Belmont </PERSON>, who lives nearby with two pre-school-age children. The shady suburb north of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> is nestled on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and marked by large homes and comfortable incomes. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Bears president <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McCaskey </PERSON> lives there, as do numerous <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> realty barons, bankers and industrialists. A survey released last year by a <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> urbanologist ranked the community of 12,482 the nation's 22nd-wealthiest suburb with an estimated per-capita income of $ 35,406
