<HEAD>Officials to Investigate Mofford Gift Purchases While Secretary of
State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `I have ..., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
statement from governor's office; picks up 3rd graf: `Mrs. Mofford
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s attorney general took initial steps Friday toward investigating Gov. Rose Mofford's expenditures of thousands of dollars in state funds on gifts and decorations when she was secretary of state. Some of the spending appears to have lacked legislative authorization, according to records and interviews with officials, although the governor and a close aide said the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> had approved the funds. Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>'s office issued a statement saying she `` stands behind'' all the expenditures. Press aide <PERSON> Vada </PERSON> <PERSON> Manager </PERSON> said the governor would not hold a news conference on the issue because, `` I do n't think there's anything serious enough to have a press conference over.'' The governor, in a brief interview with radio station <ORGANIZATION> KFYI </ORGANIZATION> said `` I never misspent a penny. It was appropriated for VIP gifts and I used it for that type of purpose. I never used anything for personal gain.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, 65, became governor April 4 when <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was removed from office upon being convicted in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> impeachment trial of misusing state funds and obstructing justice. Records examined by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> showed that Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>'s gift expenditures totaled at least $ 50,000 for her last five years as secretary of state. Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> used state funds to pay for such things as a joke-writing service and diet food as well as paintings, watches, Indian kachina dolls, clocks, flags and knickknacks, typically charging them to `` other operating expenses'' or `` supplies.'' House Speaker <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> said he would wait to hear from Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Maricopa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> before deciding whether to launch an impeachment probe. Since <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> is next in line to succeed Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, he already had turned over to <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> an investigation of her financial disclosure practices. That investigation stemmed from an AP report that while secretary of state she had failed to include a number of her business dealings in the state-required reports. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said Friday that <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> had agreed to investigate the gift expenditures as well. He added that whether any criminal or civil action will be taken will depend on what <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> finds. Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> did not respond to AP queries about the gifts and spoke only briefly to <ORGANIZATION> KFYI </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier this month, she had said that when faced with the need to present gifts to important visitors as secretary of state, she `` took care of it myself.'' `` I've paid for a lot of my dinners and all those artifacts and things that are there,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> continued. `` Only gifts _ we have a fund for VIP gifts that we are permitted to use that was appropriated by the Legislature. Other than that, I pay for it out of my own pocket.'' <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state, said the expenditures had been authorized by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> as early as 1980 when Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> requested permission to spend $ 5,000 to make some kind of presentation to visiting dignitaries `` on behalf of the state.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s official records show $ 2,400 in unspecified `` other'' expenses was approved that year and $ 2,500 in 1981. More recently, the Legislature has provided lump-sum allocations for the secretary of state's office with little direction as to how the funds are divided. The budget this year is $ 1.9 million. <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Drobny </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s staff analyst for the secretary of state's office in 1980, said she did n't believe the $ 2,400 was for gifts but that she could not recall what it was for. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> also said he did n't know the money was for gifts. He added that he could understand some of the purchases but that buying a joke service or diet food `` blows my mind.'' The state constitution bars the state from giving anything of value to an individual without public benefit, and state law makes unauthorized expenditures of public funds a felony. Mrs. <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON> said she considered that gifts Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> gave as secretary of state did result in a public benefit, because they were aimed at pleasing someone who could bring business to the state, were in recognition of service to the state or were aimed at motivating future conduct. Records for use of state funds the past five years ago show that as secretary of state, Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> spent about $ 9,000 on pens and other novelties with her name on them, about $ 6,400 on 30 watches bearing the state seal, and about $ 5,700 on kachina and other dolls and their display cases. The total also included about $ 11,000 for flags, mostly state and national, some of which were bought from unauthorized vendors at higher prices than those paid to authorized vendors for similar flags. Other expenditures included $ 203.70 for a weight-reduction product shipped to a friend and business partner of Mrs. Mofford, and $ 306 for the five years' annual renewal of a joke service that promises to supply speakers with 120 to 140 new jokes and stories a month. Mrs. <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON> called that `` probably the greatest tool in the world'' since `` nobody wants to hear a dull, totally dry speech.'' As for the diet food, Mrs. <PERSON> Osborne </PERSON> said she did n't know anything about it. A 1978 protocol-fund statute allows the governor, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> president to make gifts that promote state interests and encourage public service. It does not include the secretary of state. After she became governor, Mrs. <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON> said she wanted <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s privately raised protocol fund _ money he was convicted by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> of misusing _ placed in the state General Fund that comes from tax revenues `` I would not have a protocol fund, period,'' she said. `` I do n't want one.''
