<FIRST>r i PM-India-Sikhs     05-20 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sikhs,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ending Temple Siege Doesn't End War</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The surrender of Sikh extremists in their sacred <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> did not end the war of terror through which they hope to create a nation called <LOCATION> Khalistan </LOCATION>, the Land of the Pure. During the 10 days Sikh gunmen and their sympathizers spent inside the temple complex, surrounded by about 2,800 policemen and soldiers, their comrades killed 133 people in the holy city of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> and other parts of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. Twenty-five more people were reported killed Thursday, the day after the surrender at the temple in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. They included two Hindu priests and a Sikh holy man. It is from <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, a rich northern agricultural state, that the radicals would create <PERSON> Khalistan </PERSON>. It is the only state where Sikhs, who make up only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people, are in the majority. <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribeiro </PERSON>, former police chief of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and now security adviser to the state government, was asked if the surrender indicated an end to terrorism. He replied: `` No, far from it.'' Bomb disposal squads searched for hidden explosives Thursday in the 400-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, the holiest shrine of <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>. Police said four more bodies were found inside, bringing the death toll of the siege to 46. A committee of Sikh elders that manages the temple conferred about preparations to reopen the gold-domed shrine. Sikh extremists began fighting for a separate homeland six years ago, accusing the Hindu-dominated federal government of discrimination and of hampering economic development in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Thousands of people have been killed since then. Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> signed a peace agreement with moderate Sikhs in 1985, but it fell apart within a year. The Sikh extremists, initially blamed for scattered killings, have attacked loaded buses, sleeping villagers and congested markets in recent years. At least 1,088 people have been killed in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> so far this year, compared to 1,032 for all 1987. Most victims are Hindus, but an increasing number of Sikh moderates are being slain. Police estimate the radicals have more than 3,000 men under arms, with increasingly sophisticated weapons. The greatest fear of <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s government is that the separatist movement will become a full-scale civil war and encourage insurgencies among other minorities. `` So far, the terrorists are a small section of the population,'' one official said privately. `` We want to keep it that way.'' Support for the extremists within the Sikh community may be waning. After an army raid on the Golden Temple complex in 1984, angry Sikhs held rallies. But hardly any Sikhs objected publicly to the siege of the temple that ended Wednesday, and a gathering of Sikh temple managers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> passed a resolution Wednesday praising the government's `` rescue'' of the shrine. Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> ordered the 1984 raid to drive out extremists taking shelter in the temple. About 1,200 people were killed. Two of Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s Sikh guards assassinated her five months later. Prominent Sikhs generally believe the violence will continue until the government of <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Indira </PERSON>'s son and successor, reaches a political compromise with the militants. <PERSON> Kushwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a respected Sikh writer, urged the government recently to abandon its practice of searching for a single moderate Sikh to lead peace efforts. `` What we have to find is not a person or persons to lead the <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, but -LRB- a way -RRB- to set out principles of conduct and stick to them no matter what the immediate consequences,'' he wrote in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hindustan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. He advocated release of hundreds of Sikhs detained without trial, prosecution of Hindu politicians and others accused of instigating the anti-Sikh riots in 1984, and new investment to stimulate <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>'s faltering economy. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s 1985 accord with moderates called for settlement of land and water disputes between <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> state, investigation of the 1984 riots and speedy handling of arrest and detention cases. He put <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> under federal rule in May 1987, after the agreement had failed, but in March of this year returned to a softer approach and ordered the release from prison of militant Sikh high priest <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON>. Rode was arrested last week trying to march on the temple to end the police siege.
