<FIRST>r i PM-AnglerWars     05-20 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angler Wars,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anglers Angered Over Fishing Licenses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KILDORRERY, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like the one that got away, the Great Anglers' Strike of'88 is assured of an honorable place in the folklore of Irish fishing. It is a tale of defiance, anger and of farce tinged with menace. It invokes the memory of <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s freedom wars, reflects rural resentment against big-city bureaucrats, and climaxes with an 11th-hour truce mediated by an archbishop. And all because of a fishing license. The trouble began on New Year's Day, when a law took effect requiring anglers, for the first time, to buy licenses. At 15 pounds -LRB- $ 26.50 -RRB- for a year's trout fishing and 10 pounds -LRB- $ 15.60 -RRB- for other fish, the permits are n't exorbitant or unusual for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. But the anglers were outraged. They threatened to shut down angling and deal a severe blow to western <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s multimillion dollar tourism industry unless the license law was withdrawn. The government refused, and in mid-April the strike began. Signs popped up along roads and at fishing venues saying `` No Rod License'' and `` Licensed Anglers Not Welcome Here.'' Angling clubs declared their waters off-limits to fishers. Hotels told guests with bookings to stay away. Fishing stores refused to sell the licenses. Dark tales circulated of anglers' car tires being slashed and a fishing boat being sawed in half. True or not, they had the desired effect. By mid-May, as the lakes and rivers swarmed with trout feasting on the newly hatched mayflies, not an angler was in sight, and all angling competitions were canceled. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Munster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trout </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anglers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, says it's not the money, but the principle. `` We believe we have a God-given right to fish,'' said the 54-year-old pub owner, smacking the dashboard of his car. `` I want to hand down to my children and grandchildren what my forefathers gave to me _ the right to fish over these waters for free.'' In the tiny <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cork </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Kildorrery </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>' friend <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> harked back 70 years to <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s war for independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` My father and <PERSON> Dick </PERSON>'s father put their lives on the line fighting for our freedom, and freedom includes the right to fish,'' he said. `` It's a battle for control,'' <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> said. `` We anglers have developed these waters, cleaned up pollution, restocked them, without one penny in government aid, and we want to keep it that way.'' Commented lawmaker <PERSON> Enda </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON>: `` In the land of Capt. -LRB- Charles -RRB- <PERSON> Boycott </PERSON>, attitudes have become deeply entrenched,'' a reference to the 19th-century land agent who lost his crops to a peasants' boycott and gave his name to the English language The debt-ridden economy urgently needs cash, and the government sees nothing wrong with the angling licenses. But its attitude is under attack. `` It is government by diktat rather than by any sort of consensus,'' charged the <ORGANIZATION> Cork </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION>. `` This whole matter has been handled in a very nonsensical manner.'' Indeed, the law passed so quickly and with so little fanfare that the government tourism agency did n't have time to alter its latest promotional literature, which still says Irish waters are license-free. Meanwhile, the $ 60 million annual tourism industry in western <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> says hotels catering to anglers have been hit hard by cancellations. `` We are facing ruin at the moment,'' said <PERSON> June </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodgson </PERSON>, who runs a classy anglers' hotel on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Corrib </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION>. `` It's devastating, heartbreaking to look out over an empty lake and see no boats,'' she said Tuesday. Unbeknownst to her, however, higher powers were working to get the anglers and the government off the hook. Late Wednesday, the Archbishop of <LOCATION> Tuam </LOCATION>, Dr. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>, announced he had secretly negotiated a deal whereby the licensing law would not be implemented until further discussion. <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuck </PERSON> of the Anti-Rod-Licensing Campaign saw this as a face-saving compromise and said the boats would return to Corrib later. But <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> remained suspicious. `` I do n't see any government commitment to repeal the law, so for the time being our strike is still on,'' he said. `` This is a tax on our sport,'' he said. `` If they get away with this, next year it'll be the tennis racket, then the golf club, then the hurling stick. You know governments. Once they get one leg in, it's all over. Next year they'll double it, then treble it.''
</TEXT>
