<HEAD>Soft Drink Execs Convicted Of Price Fixing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former president of a <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> bottler and the chairman of the company that once owned a rival <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> bottling operation have been convicted of price fixing by a federal jury. Sentencing for <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harford </PERSON>, former president of <ORGANIZATION> Mid-Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of Silver Spring, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON>, chairman of the board of <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Cheverly </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, has not been set. The two face a maximum of three years in prison. They were convicted Thursday of conspiring to set the wholesale price of their products between February 1983 and the fall of 1985. <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beverage </ORGANIZATION> was the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bottling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In the six-week trial, prosecutors sought to show that both companies enjoyed higher profits because of the artifical inflation of their wholesale prices. They provided no estimate of cost to the consumer. `` They did n't want a price war ... and gave a green light to price-fixing,'' said assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> of the defendants. A third executive indicted, <PERSON> Odis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, vice president of <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION>, pleaded guilty March 22 to one count of price fixing. Prosecutors said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> met numerous times with other soft-drink executives to scheme about boosting wholesale prices of both <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>. The defense contended that <PERSON> Harford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lapides </PERSON> were unaware of what was happening, and were hostile competitors who had fought each other in court and in the marketplace. The indictments came out of a wide-ranging <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> probe of the soft drink industry. In March, <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> agreed to refund $ 45,000 to state and local governments for cola bought by school districts during the time of the alleged price fixing.
