<FIRST>r a AM-CopIndicted     05-20 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cop Indicted,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Grand Jury Indicts Former Cop in 1983 Motorcycle Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A white former police officer, acquitted of state charges in the 1983 shooting death of a black man, was indicted Thursday by a federal grand jury for civil rights violations in the same shooting. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Volz </PERSON> said the indictment charges <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> with shooting <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Glover </PERSON>, 18, in the back on Aug. 31, 1983. The federal charges accuse <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> of violating <PERSON> Glover </PERSON>'s civil rights. The maximum penalty in the federal case would be life in prison. <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemann </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, said he would try to get the indictment dismissed on the grounds that it subjects <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> to double jeopardy. <PERSON> Volz </PERSON> would not say whether any new evidence was uncovered in the federal investigation. Asked why it took so long to bring the federal charges, <PERSON> Volz </PERSON> would say only that prosecutors had been watching post-trial developments and felt the time finally had come to move on the case. He said federal officials were interested in the case because `` the boy was shot in the back riding on the back of a motorcycle fleeing from what was at worst a traffic arrest.'' Also, <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> and his partner admitted that they planted a gun near the scene to make it appear that the shooting was in self-defense, he said. <PERSON> Glover </PERSON>, the son of a policewoman, was a passenger behind the driver of a speeding motocycle that <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> and his partner were chasing. <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> testified during the trial that he thought he was being fired upon and that his own gun went off when the police car accelerated. His partner, who testified in exchange for immunity, said no one fired from the cycle. <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON>, a nine-year officer, was suspended from the police force after the shooting and was fired three months later. He was charged in state court and convicted of second-degree murder in 1984. The verdict was overturned by the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 and <PERSON> Rosiere </PERSON> was aquitted in a second trial in 1986. He works as a carpenter in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>.
