<HEAD>Nevada Explosion Casts Doubt On Shuttle Schedule After August</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> still hopes to launch the first post-Challenger space shuttle in August, but the agency is uncertain whether it can meet a goal of nine flights next year, the head of the shuttle program says. The reason for the doubt is the explosion that destroyed the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, on May 4. The explosion eliminated the source of half the nation's supply of a chemical used for the shuttle boosters and some other rockets A second plant in <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION>, has shut down for inspections to see that it is safe. Pacific Engineering and <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION> were the only American companies manufacturing ammonium perchlorate, an oxidizer. The oxidizer makes sure the solid rocket fuel burns evenly. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Truly </PERSON>, associate administrator for space flight of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday that rocket-maker <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> has enough ammonium perchlorate on hand for four flights and there is enough on hand for a fifth rocket set. The Titan 4 also uses ammonium perchlorate. The chemical, in the form of white crystals, is taken by rail car to <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s plant in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, mixed there, and poured into the segments that make the booster rockets. `` The issue will first come up in 1989, but we're not certain there is going to be an impact in 1989 until we get together with the <ORGANIZATION> DOD </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- to match requirements and availability,'' Truly said. He said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> will have to decide how to divide up the output of <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION>. He said the first post-Challenger flight still is on schedule for launch in late August. He insisted the agency had not set a firm date but is working toward a target of Aug. 22. Pacific Engineering said the explosion, which killed two people and injured 326 was caused by a natural gas leak. Pacific Engineering and <ORGANIZATION> Kerr-McGee </ORGANIZATION> each produced 30 million pounds per year of ammonium perchlorate. <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said the company has n't ruled out buying ammonium perchlorate from foreign firms but added: `` The rest of the world supply is pretty meager I've seen estimates of worldwide production of nine million pounds a year.'' A pair of shuttle booster rockets uses 1.5 million pounds of ammonium perchlorate per flight.
