<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s spokesman says the administration is wary of giving military personnel drug-trafficking arrest powers because `` you cross an enormous bridge when you move them'' to an enforcement role. Spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> on Thursday did not directly oppose a bill passed overwhelmingly by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to make arrests on the high seas, but he said the administration is `` very cautious in that area.'' `` I think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people would want us to be cautious,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` But that does not diminish the idea that there are expanded roles for the military.'' <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, oppose attempts by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to substantially change a military role which now consists primarily of surveillance. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> was asked about a change <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> made in a speech Wednesday on the subject. The prepared remarks had called for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to say he had directed <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> to search for `` creative solutions on how we can better use military resources and technologies to detect and interdict drugs coming into this country.'' But when he actually delivered the speech, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> changed that line to say he wanted <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> to find better ways for the military `` to detect drugs and support civil law enforcement agencies in interdiction.'' Asked about the significance of the change, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` There is a very great concern about what it means to make law enforcement officers out of the military.'' `` You cross an enormous bridge when you move them from providing military support and surveillance and physical interdiction efforts to making arrests and legal judgments and so forth,'' he said. `` As I think it was, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> -RRB- the other day said, ` The first time an F-15 shoots down a dentist because his -LRB- airplane -RRB- radio does n't work, you begin to understand the dimensions of the problem.'' The chamber last Friday voted 83-6 for an amendment outlining a wide-ranging anti-drug role for the military. The proposal calls for more surveillance by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> planes, increased anti-drug activity by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and more <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> helicopters for the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The most controversial provision would require <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels to track suspected drug boats and would allow <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers to arrest suspected drug traffickers in international waters. The officers would be temporarily `` deputized'' by <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officers who would be aboard for that purpose. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, however, likened the drug trade to `` a 30-foot tidal wave hitting a 25-foot wall'' and said, `` The fact is that interdiction is never going to solve the problem without cutting the demand.''
