<HEAD>Central Bank Governor Resigns; Economic Outlook Grim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The governor of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has resigned in the face of mounting economic pressures in this <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> nation, where inflation has soared to 50 percent. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON> gave no explanation for his action Thursday. The economist appeared briefly at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION>, the seat of government, to deliver a letter of resignation to the government of President <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Balaguer </PERSON>. <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON>, 50, has disagreed with some of <PERSON> Balaguer </PERSON>'s solutions for stimulating the economy in this nation of 6.5 million people. `` Unfortunately, I am not a politician and I can not be in these political fights,'' <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON> said in a brief interview at the National Palace. By late afternoon, the government had made no comment nor named a replacement. <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON> is the second <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> governor to resign since <PERSON> Balaguer </PERSON> was elected in May 1986. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> quit in November after suggesting that repayments on the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>'s $ 4 billion debt be limited to 10 percent of export earnings. Last year, debt repayments amounted $ 750 million, or more than the value of total exports. <PERSON> Saladin </PERSON> has chafed at <PERSON> Balaguer </PERSON>'s policy to stimulate the economy by pumping $ 600 million into public works. About 210,000 jobs have been created and economic growth is projected at 8 percent this year, but there have been unwelcome side-effects. Inflation has soared to 50 percent, private economists estimate. The foreign exchange value of the peso has dropped by about 20 percent to 19 cents since lat