<FIRST>r w PM-Colleges-Crash     05-20 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colleges-Crash,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>College Endowments Suffer As Result Of Market Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A college business group says 50 of the wealthiest American universities lost 13.1 percent of their endowments in the last quarter of 1987 as a result of the stock market crash. By comparison, common stocks overall dropped 22.6 percent during the final three months of 1987, as measured by the Standard and Poor's 500, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Officers </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The group, which has tracked endowments since 1974, said the downturn came after an excellent year for the campus funds, including a gain of nearly 25 percent in the stock market during the 12 months that ended on June 30, 1987. The typical campus had little more than half its endowment invested in stocks. The overall return on their holdings in the 1986-87 academic year was 13.9 percent, the business officers said. In arriving at the 13.9 percent figure, the association used data supplied by 296 colleges and universities with endowments ranging from $ 1.5 million for <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> to $ 4 billion for <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. The market value of the endowments of all 296 institutions was $ 47.9 billion at mid-year. The report did not provide a cumulative figure for after the crash. There are more than 3,000 colleges and universities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The association study covers most of those with endowments of $ 1 million or more. While the group normally reports trends from July of one year through June of the next, it commissioned a special analysis by <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> on the impact of the Oct. 19 stock market crash, when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> Industrial Average of 30 industrial stocks fell 508 points. `` The October 1987 stock market tumble caused 50 college and university endowments of $ 100 million or more to fall an average of 13.1 percent in the fourth quarter of the calendar year,'' said the study, reported in the May issue of Business Officer, an association magazine. After `` the market meltdown,'' those 50 universities engaged in a `` modest repositioning,'' it said. The 50 were not named, and no figures were given on where their endowments stood after the tumble. Between Sept. 30 and Dec. 31, their asset allocations went from 63 percent to 57 percent stocks, from 27 percent to 32 percent bonds and from 10 percent to 11 percent cash. At mid-year, among all 296 colleges and universities, the average investment pool was composed of 54.2 percent stocks, 29.4 percent bonds, 12.7 percent cash and equivalents, 1.9 percent real estate and 1.8 percent other assets. Ten endowments were worth $ 1 billion or more last summer. They were: <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, $ 4.02 billion; <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> system, $ 2.8 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.3 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, $ 2.1 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.7 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.4 billion; <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> system, $ 1.21 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.2 billion; <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.17 billion; and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, $ 1.12 billion.
