<FIRST>r w PM-Shoppers-Nutrition     05-20 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shoppers-Nutrition,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoppers Concern Over Nutrition Rising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More women than men say they are very concerned about eating the right foods, and old people are more concerned than any other age group, a survey on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> shoppers reports. The annual survey of shoppers by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a nonprofit association representing the food industry, found `` dynamic increases'' in customer awareness of health issues such as fat, salt and sugar content. In the survey in January of 1,019 shoppers, 58 percent of the women said they were very concerned about nutrition, compared with 48 percent of men. Some 59 percent of people without children said they were very concerned about nutrition, compared with 52 percent of those who had children at home. The share who said they were very concerned about nutrition was largest among senior citizens, at 72 percent of people aged 65 and over. Those aged 18 to 24 showed the least interest, 33 percent being very concerned. The share very concerned about nutrition peaked in the South at 60 percent, followed by 56 percent in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, 54 percent in the East and 52 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. `` People are remarkably knowledgeable and sophisticated about health and nutrition issues,'' <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammonds </PERSON>, a vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday. They are adjusting their diets, doing less frying and more broiling of foods, seeking more fresh fruits, he said. Some 27 percent of supermarket shoppers said they are concerned about fat in their foods, up from 16 percent just a year ago and 9 percent in 1983, the institute said. And worry about cholesterol jumped eight points from 14 percent to 22 percent in the past year, the institute said. It rated 5 percent in 1983. `` I think the important thing is that the numbers are increasing. ... It shows more and more people are learning that fatty foods can contribute to heart disease, obesity and possibly colon and breast cancer,'' said <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebman </PERSON>, nutrition director for the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interest </ORGANIZATION>, a consumer-oriented health advocacy group. `` More and more people have gotten the message that they should cut back on fat, but ... people need help translating principles into breakfast, lunch and dinner,'' she said. <PERSON> Liebman </PERSON> urged food manufacturers to provide clearer labeling, with guidance such as `` high, low or medium'' fat, in addition to the actual measurement. However, consumer concern does n't necessarily translate into action. Just last week Prevention magazine's annual health study disclosed that 54 percent of people polled said they were trying to reduce the fat in their diets, a decline from 56 percent a year earlier. Even so, <PERSON> Hammonds </PERSON> stressed that the food industry is responding to consumer concerns. In recent years farmers have begun raising leaner hogs than in the past, markets are trimming more of the fat from meats and offering leaner meat cuts, and the government has changed grading standards to make leaner meats more attractive, he pointed out. Indeed, a coalition of more than a dozen consumer health groups is expected to release a study shortly praising major food manufacturers and restaurant chains for reducing their use of saturated fats. While more than one-quarter of shoppers expressed concern about fat, the institute found that as many as half said they turned to labels for information on these and other ingredients. Some 46 percent of shoppers said they looked on food labels for fat and protein content of foods. Other topics gaining attention of consumers included `` freshness and purity,'' up 7 points from last year to 15 percent saying they are concerned. Salt and sugar each gained 4 percentage points, to 26 percent and 20 percent respectively. Worry about preservatives was up 2 points to 16 percent and chemical additives rose 1 point to 14 percent. Concern about vitamin content was unchanged at 21 percent, as was the 14 percent rating for calories. The findings were reported in the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 edition of `` Trends: Consumer Attitudes & amp; The Supermarket.'' The margin of error for the sample generally ranges between 2 and 3 percentage points.
