<HEAD>US Funds Monitoring Commission, Blasts Sandinistas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has approved $ 10 million to monitor compliance with the Nicaraguan peace process, drawing congressional criticism for taking so long to decide how to use the money. The money was part of a $ 48 million package approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in late March, a week after <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government and the Contra rebels signed a temporary truce at <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. That agreement called for the creation of a verification commission to monitor compliance with the accord. Of the funds, $ 8 million will go for activities of <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON>, secretary general of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION>, and $ 2 million for Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, leader of the Nicaraguan <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. The allocations are based on a budget submitted by the commission to which the two men belong. Shortly after the grant was announced, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, criticized the administration for taking six weeks to determine how to spend the funds. Other Democrats have made the same criticism. Money for the verification commission had been held up because the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> were unable to agree on a proposal that met <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goverment accounting requirements. This drew an angry reaction from Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., who said that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were demanding an elaborate accounting system from the <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> on the one hand while, on the other, they were giving money to the Contras and letting it `` simply disappear into the jungle. In announcing the grant, the administration launched a harsh attack on the Sandinista government. The administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, charged that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> had engaged in a campaign of `` harassment and intimidation'' and `` menacing militarism'' in apparent violation of agreements signed by Sandinista authorities. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> said in letters to <PERSON> Baena </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> and <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo: `` Anyone who shares our interest in peace, democracy and reconciliation in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> must be greatly alarmed by the recent crackdown on human rights and civil liberties by the Sandinista government.'' `` This barrage of harassment and intimidation makes it clear that the verification commission must fully monitor the very fundamental issues of democracy, civil liberties and human rights.'' <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> told the commission members that a series of incidents in recent weeks has undermined `` the process of reconciliation to which the Nicaraguan government committed itself.'' He said the process is being further scuttled by the Nicaraguan government's `` menacing militarism.'' He cited a statement by <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> in which he threatened the Contras with `` actions on a scale never before seen in this war.'' <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> also said Nicaraguan authorities have placed severe limitations on press freedom and that more than 30 persons supporting construction workers conducting a hunger strike were arrested. The Sandinistas and the Contras are attempting to negotiate a permanent settlement but have made little progress. The deadline for reaching an agreement is June 1.
