<FIRST>r i PM-Baker-Financial     05-20 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Financial,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Rules Out Sweeping Changes In World Monetary System</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release at 2:30 a.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-World Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The global economy is changing too rapidly for governments to successfully impose major changes in the way they manage exchange rates, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said today. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said he favors gradual, step-by-step efforts to improve coordination of monetary policy among the major industrialized countries. He cited as an example a possible broadening of coordination on national tax reform and deregulation of financial and labor markets. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also could work more closely with its major trading partners in monitoring the performance of their economies, he said. But in remarks prepared for delivery to the Council on Foreign Relations, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> ruled out any `` sweeping, revolutionary changes in the system.'' His appearance before the council was closed to the news media. Copies of his speech were made available in advance. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> met on Wednesday and Thursday in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> with trade and finance ministers from the 24 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. `` An attempt to make an abrupt or major change in the structure of the system by imposing a detailed set of formal constraints might well be viewed by the markets as overly ambitious and unsustainable,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` The global economy is too dynamic, and the forces of change too strong, to be able to look ahead with great certainty and envision a highly defined international monetary structure that will fit the world economy of 1995 as well as that of 2005,'' he added. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told reporters after the <ORGANIZATION> OECD </ORGANIZATION> meeting Thursday that the seven largest industrial countries were pleased with the relative stability of exchange rates since last December, when they jointly bought massive amounts of dollars in the open market in order to halt its steep decline. `` We see no reason to believe that that wo n't continue,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. In his speech to the foreign relations group, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the major economic powers' efforts since 1985 to improve monetary coordination had been a remarkable, although incomplete, success. `` I strongly suspect the world economy is better off today than we would have been had we not followed this course,'' he said. Some government officials and private experts have said the world monetary system should undergo more radical reforms than suggested by <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. A study published earlier this month by the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said existing international agreements on ways of keeping exchange rates stable were `` agonizingly fragile.'' The issue of reforms to the world monetary system is expected to be discussed at a June 19-21 summit meeting in Tornoto of leaders from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
