<FIRST>r w PM-HomeEquityLoans     05-20 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Equity Loans,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Clears Bill To Strengthen Disclosure Requirements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House is expected to act quickly on legislation requiring lenders to make full disclosure of what one of the sponsors calls `` the potential pitfalls'' of home equity loans. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, a major sponsor of the bill, said he expected it to become law rapidly after clearing the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday by a unanimous voice vote. He noted the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has already approved a similar, but less stringent, measure. `` Home equity loans can be like a loaded pistol,'' said <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON>. `` Consumers need to beware or they can blow up in their face.'' The legislation requires lenders to make full disclosure on home equity loan accounts so that new applicants can know exactly what it is they are applying for. Lenders would have to provide information on the annual interest percentage rate, any fees associated with the loan, a series of warnings about the risks involved and a description of repayment options. `` With the passage of the ... bill, the committee is taking the mystery out of the home equity loans and hopefully providing consumers with a guide to the potential pitfalls of home equity loans,'' he said. Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Banking consumer affairs subcommittee which handled the bill, echoed the sentiments of <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> and other proponents of the legislation `` This legislation enables consumers to know that home equity loans have risks as well as benefits,'' <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> said. `` This legislation will assure that they receive, at the time of application, all the information necessary to make an informed decision, whether to apply for such a loan. `` In addition, it will strictly limit areas which were susceptible to abuse by the unilateral action of creditors.'' The bill also provides for other consumer protections: - A prohibition on a creditor unilaterally changing the terms of the loan contract - Requiring the use of publicly available indexes outside the control of the lender when the rate of interest varies - Restrictions on the lender from calling in the loan before the term of the loan - A right to obtain a refund of application fees if the lender changes the terms after an application is submitted but before the account is opened The committee's action was lauded by consumer organizations, but the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said the `` disclosure and advertising provisions are impractical. They will result in an unnecessary overload of information for consumers, and they will severely limit the creditors' ability to design informative advertisements.'' Home equity loans - a line of credit available to borrowers who provide their homes as collateral - have grown more popular in recent years, especially since interest on them is tax deductible in most cases. Consumer groups report that home equity lending doubled between 1986 and 1987 from $ 40 billion to $ 80 billion.
</TEXT>
