<FIRST>r w PM-Teamsters-Truckers     05-20 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters-Truckers,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teamsters Accept Contract Although Truckers Voted Against It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union accepted a new trucking industry contract that was overwhelmingly rejected in rank-and-file balloting, with a <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> official saying members who did n't vote probably favored it. The union said Thursday that 64,101 truckers voted to turn down the proposed three-year National Master Freight Agreement while 36,782 supported the new proposal. The 63.5 percent opposition vote fell short of the two-thirds voting majority needed under Teamster bylaws to reject a contract and authorize a strike. Under the union's constitution, 66.66 percent of those voting have to turn down a proposed contract or it goes into effect automatically. `` Since the constitution requires that the final offer be accepted as a result of failure to reject by two-thirds vote, any strike or work stoppage will be a violation of the agreement and have serious consequences,'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Yager </PERSON>, chairman of the union negotiating committee, said in a statement. <PERSON> Yager </PERSON> said over 57 percent of the ballots mailed out were not returned. He maintained that it was likely the 80,000 members who did not return ballots were satisfied with the final offer. `` If not, they would have cast ballots rejecting the contract,'' he said. The new contract provides annual 35-cents-an-hour wage gains over the next three years to some 200,000 workers. The contract raises the base rate for truck drivers from the current $ 14.71 an hour to $ 15.06 an hour retroactive to April 1. This would be followed by similar 35-cent hourly raises in 1989 and 1990. The contract proved unpopular with union truck drivers because of certain changes in work rules. Locals were upset over a provision of the agreement that would require all Teamsters members at a trucking company that is losing money to give back 15 percent of their pay in exchange for a promised share of any future profits if 75 percent of the union members vote to do so. Another provision could force drivers to pay for loss of freight or for truck damage if their company proves gross negligence.
</TEXT>
