<FIRST>r w PM-NCI-BreastCancer     05-20 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NCI-Breast Cancer,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Show Benefits Of Additional Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Women with early stage breast cancer would benefit from treatment in addition to initial surgery or radiation therapy, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> says, citing three studies that have yet to be published. Such additional treatment _ chemotherapy or hormonal therapy or both _ has been the institution's formal recommendation for the past two years in cases involving more advanced breast cancer. The <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> announcement Thursday shows the institute views the new findings significant enough to publicize before they are formally published in a medical journal or presented at a scientific meeting. Women with early stage breast cancer _ before it has spread to lymph nodes under the arm _ have been regarded as having a relatively favorable prognosis after primary treatment, but it is now recognized that up to 30 percent have recurrences of their cancer, the <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The richness of the clinical evidence from a variety of trials now shows that this outlook can be improved upon,'' <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> Director Dr. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said. The data that prompted the <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION>'s statement were presented to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> on May 9 and a special clinical alert was mailed Monday to 13,000 cancer specialists and cancer organizations. `` Each year more than 60,000 women in this country are diagnosed with node-negative breast cancer ... and we can not delay informing them and their physicians that additional treatment beyond surgery and-or radiotherapy may be beneficial,'' <PERSON> DeVita </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> researcher, said future <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> studies will focus on which forms of additional treatment are best, rather than whether there is a benefit from any such treatment. It is estimated that 135,000 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women will get breast cancer this year and that 42,000 will die from it. One in 10 women will develop breast cancer in her lifetime. `` The emerging information from the three <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> studies is consistent with a more mature body of information from <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> investigators,'' the <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> announcement said. One <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> study of 679 patients found 80 percent of those given additional treatment were cancer-free after four years compared with 71 percent who were not given additional treatment. The other study involved 2,644 patients in which 82 percent of those given additional treatment were cancer-free after four years compared with 77 percent of those receiving a placebo. The third involved about 350 patients and found 84 percent of those given additional treatment cancer-free after three years compared with 67 percent of those given a placebo.
</TEXT>
