<HEAD>House Panel OKs $14.3 Billion Foreign Aid Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House has been given a $ 14.3 billion foreign aid bill that represents a 2 percent increase over last year's level and largely continues current programs. On a voice vote Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved without amendment the bill passed earlier this month by its foreign operations subcommittee. The bill covers the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. There was little debate on the measure because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has little flexibility in dealing with appropriations as a result of budget-cutting agreements reached late last year. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> again would receive more than any other country under the bill _ some $ 1.8 billion in military aid and $ 1.2 billion in economic assistance. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, which is favored for making peace with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, receives the second-largest amount _ $ 1.3 billion in military assistance and $ 815 million in economic aid. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which has been regarded as a front-line country because of the Soviet occupation of neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, would receive $ 220 million in economic aid and $ 240 million in forgiven loans for purchase of military goods. The <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> would receive $ 124 million in economic aid and $ 125 million in military aid. Some $ 90 million in economic support and $ 655 million in economic development money would be used for African countries. In <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> would get $ 85 million in economic aid, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> $ 90 million, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> $ 185 million and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> $ 80 million. Military aid for those and other countries was not earmarked, but would come out of separate military aid and credit accounts. The bill also would give economic aid of $ 40 million to <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>; $ 20 million to <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>; $ 10 million to <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>; $ 15 million to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>; between $ 10 million and $ 35 million for <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>; and $ 2 million for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s Solidarity trade union. Some $ 34 million would be set aside for <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> development projects, of which $ 11 million is for projects in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and $ 23 million for those in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The bill would allocate $ 150 million to the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, $ 101 million for international narcotics control, $ 362 million for migration and refugee assistance, $ 35 million for the prevention of AIDS worldwide and $ 254 million to pay past-due debts of international financial institutions. It would send $ 217 million to support a long list of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> organizations, and stipulate that the money for <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> must be obligated within 30 days of passage of the bill, or the administration would suffer an automatic cut of $ 50 million in money for military aid. It is up to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to decide how to divide up the balance of funds for nations not specifically mentioned in the bill. About 100 countries receive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid directly.
