<HEAD>Prospective Jurors Screened As Mecham Criminal Trial Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorneys for <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> planned to spend the weekend weeding out obviously biased candidates for the jury in the former governor's criminal trial on charges he concealed a campaign loan. The trial began Thursday, when 100 prospective jurors were sworn in and filled out long questionnaires aimed in part at eliminating people who may have been influenced by the publicity surrounding the case. `` There goes my weekend,'' said <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s defense lawyer, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, noting that attorneys on both sides hope to analyze the forms before meeting again Monday. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, 64, and his brother, <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, are charged with concealing the $ 350,000 campaign loan by failing to report it on the former governor's campaign or personal finance statements. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, a Republican, is charged with six felony counts of perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three similar counts. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was removed from office last month when the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted him on impeachment charges. He could face up to 22 years in prison if convicted of all six counts in the trial, while his brother could be sentenced to up to 9 -LCB- years if convicted on the three counts he faces. Neither attended Thursday's initial session in <ORGANIZATION> Maricopa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> probably will attend court next week, after the questioning of potential jurors begins. The questionnaire was worked out by the prosecution, defense and trial Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. Among the 99 questions were whether the panelists know anyone involved in the case, whether they signed or circulated petitions for or against <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> while he was governor and whether they belong to the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Birch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. Also, they were asked whether they knew anyone on a long list of people associated with <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> or his criminal case. The former governor has refused to predict whether he will fare better in court than at his impeachment trial. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> removed <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> on April 4, 15 months into his first term, by convicting him of trying to thwart a death threat investigation and of misusing $ 80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning the money to his auto dealership. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was also impeached on charges of concealing the $ 350,000 loan, but the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> decided not to consider that charge for fear of prejudicing <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s criminal trial. Prosecutors said the Mechams failed to report the loan from <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfson </PERSON> until after a newspaper reported it in October 1987. On Wednesday, a state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice refused a defense request to delay the trial until the high court considers a defense motion to return the charges to the grand jury. The <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is to hear arguments on that issue June 1. The defense filed two new motions, released Thursday. One asks the judge to dismiss the charges based on a claim that the campaign and personal finance reporting laws are unconstitutionally `` vague, ambiguous, imprecise and overbroad.'' The other asks that the charges be remanded to the grand jury for a new finding of whether probable cause exists. That motion argued that grand jury materials were improperly turned over to the prosecutors in <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s impeachment trial. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> did not schedule arguments on the motions.
