<HEAD>14 More Deaths Blamed On Sikhs; Temple Cleaning Nearly Complete</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh radicals were blamed for the killings of 14 more people in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. At the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, crews worked today to clear <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine of debris from a 10-day siege by security forces. Five of the victims killed Thursday night in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state were Hindu migrant workers from the eastern state of <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION>. Police said the workers were lined up against a wall and shot by eight Sikh gunmen, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The killings occurred in <LOCATION> Chinna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Karam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Singh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> village </LOCATION>, 18 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. It was the second attack on migrant workers this week, suggesting that the extremists are trying to undercut agriculture, the mainstay of this northern state's economy. On Tuesday night, Sikh gunmen killed more than 30 Hindu workers as they slept at a camp near the state capital of <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. Other deaths reported Thursday night which police blamed on Sikhs included five people killed in a village in <LOCATION> Jalandhar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> and four shot to death as they waited for a bus in <LOCATION> Bhatinda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>. The deaths raised to more than 1,100 the number of people killed by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> extremists in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> this year. In all of 1987, about 1,030 people were slain. Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for more political autonomy or an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, where they are a majority. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people and claim they are discriminated against by the nation's majority Hindus State-run <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> today quoted an unidentified government official in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> as saying cleaning was nearly complete at the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> and `` steps are being taken to restore traditional rituals.'' The government siege of the temple ended Wednesday with the surrender of the last Sikh extremists. Police cordoned off the complex May 9 after radicals inside fired on police officers conducting an inspection outside its walls, wounding five of them. Rituals at the golden-domed temple include a continuous reading of the Sikh holy book, the Guru <PERSON> Granth </PERSON> <PERSON> Sahib </PERSON>, and the singing of hymns. <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION> was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam. Visitors to the inner sanctum of the temple often take a ceremonial dip in the surrounding pool, which is considered sacred. On Thursday, bomb disposal squads searched the temple to make sure the surrendering extremists did not leave explosives behind. There were no reports of any explosives being found.
