ef Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorie </PERSON> said the possibility of a political defeat in the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> case has crushed his spirit and that of other prosecutors and agents in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> who worked on the case. `` We've spent a lot of time and effort making this case,'' he said. `` The assistants who worked on the case in this office and myself ... would certainly be most disappointed if the case is not allowed to go forward.'' Other prosecutors, however, had mixed reactions to the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> negotiations. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Senatore </PERSON>, a prosecutor in the public corruption section, said he differentiates between `` any political decisions that go on in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'' and `` my job of fighting crime here in this district.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted in February in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> on drug and racketeering charges. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is conducting negotiations to drop the charges in exchange for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s agreement to step aside as leader of the troubled nation
