<HEAD>Lawyers Say Israel Can't Handle Flood of Arab Prisoners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th, `Army officials...' to UPDATE with
comments from army official; PICKS up 9th pvs: `A military...';
INSERTS 1 graf after 22nd, `Israel officials...' with soldiers
investigated; PICKS up 23rd pvs: `In another...' Minor editing to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers for detained Palestinians claimed the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> military justice system has buckled under a flood of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> inmates, but army sources said prisons will be centralized and computerized for efficiency. Many of the thousands of Palestinians imprisoned during the 5-month-old uprising in the occupied lands are held incommunicado for weeks or miss court appearances because authorities ca n't locate them, their lawyers said Thursday `` It's a big mess,'' Israeli lawyer <PERSON> Lea </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsemel </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` The army is completely inefficient.'' Also Thursday, left-wing Israeli legislator <PERSON> Dedi </PERSON> <PERSON> Zucker </PERSON> issued new figures on detentions. He said 1,900 Arabs _ one in every 200 men over 18 _ are being held in jail for six months without trial. Another 8,100 Palestinians are in prison awaiting trial or serving sentences for specific charges, <PERSON> Zucker </PERSON> said. Similar figures were released by Law in the Service of Man, a human rights monitoring group founded by <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> lawyers. The organization said between 7,000 and 9,000 Palestinians are in jails, in addition to about 2,000 administrative detainees held without trial. Since the uprising started Dec. 8, 17,000 Palestinians _ 4 percent of the male population over 14 _ have been detained, said <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuttab </PERSON>, a lawyer and member of the human rights group. <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officials refused comment, saying they had to check their detention figures. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio today quoted the army legal adviser in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, Lt. Col. <PERSON> Dudu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yahav </PERSON>, a saying 1,800 Palestinians were being held without trial in administrative detention. Most are leaders of the outlawed youth group <ORGANIZATION> Shabibe </ORGANIZATION>, which is linked to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s mainstream <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION> faction, <PERSON> Yahav </PERSON> was quoted as saying. He said most detainees were being held without trial because there was insufficient evidence to bring them to court. A military prosecutor said last week that 5,000 Palestinians were being held, including 1,700 in administrative detention. According to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures, 191 Palestinians have been killed since anti-occupation protests began in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Two Israelis also have died. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> seized the lands from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. The army has built five detention centers in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the occupied lands to accommodate those detained during the unrest and has housed some detainees in 17 other prisons. A military source said Thursday that the army is adopting several measures to make the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> prison system more efficient. The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the army plans to appoint a high-ranking officer to oversee all prisons in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, install a computer in each facility to keep track of prisoners, and close smaller detention centers. And a senior officer in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s central command, identified only as Lt. Col. <PERSON> Shuki </PERSON>, was quoted as saying that detainees with the same legal status will be housed in the same prison. All administrative detainees will be moved to a prison camp in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s southern <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION>, the domestic <ORGANIZATION> Itim </ORGANIZATION> news agency quoted <PERSON> Shuki </PERSON> as saying. Lawyers for Palestinian prisoners were skeptical about the plans. `` We have filed many complaints, and now they say they are going to organize everything,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Tsemel </PERSON>. `` We've been hearing this for two months.'' Ms. <PERSON> Tsemel </PERSON> said she and several colleagues sent a letter to the army on Wednesday saying the lawyers strike if the situation does not improve. Lawyer <PERSON> Felicia </PERSON> <PERSON> Langer </PERSON>, who has represented more than 100 Palestinians, said she often searched for clients two or three weeks before prison authorities located them. `` Even those who are charged are sometimes not brought to court on the date of their trial,'' Ms. <PERSON> Langer </PERSON> added. `` The only thing that will improve the situation is to release people and not to treat them as animals, dehumanize them,'' she added. Israeli officials have denied allegations of mistreatment and inefficiency. <PERSON> Shuki </PERSON> was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> today as saying that three soldiers were investigated recently on charges they mistreated prisoners, and three detainees were released after a probe showed they were being held without justification. In another development Thursday, the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s military government permitted reunification of 40 Palestinian families as a goodwill gesture. The government applies stringent standards in issuing residency permits, often granting only temporary tourist visas to foreign-born spouses of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> residents. As a result, hundreds of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> families are separated.
