 are discriminated against in jobs and education. Tamil militants have been waging a guerrilla war against the government and Sinhalese civilians for nearly five years. The rebels rejected the peace accord, which provides greater autonomy in Tamil-populated areas if the guerrillas surrender their weapons. Sinhalese militants also reject the accord, saying it gives too much to the Tamils. To enforce the accord, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has sent more than 50,000 soldiers to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, an island off its southern coast, but Tamil militants are now fighting the Indian troops. On May 10, the government lifted a five-year ban on the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s political activities after announcing it had signed a peace agreement with the Sinhalese radicals The group denied reaching such an agreement and has continued attacks on Sinhalese politicians.
