<HEAD>Fire Marshal Says Caged Fuel Tank Would Not Have Helped in Bus
Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A protective cage like those required on newer buses would not have prevented the fuel tank of a church bus from being punctured in a fiery crash that claimed 27 lives, the state fire marshal says. Fire Marshal <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the location of a three-inch gash on the front of the 60-gallon tank and pictures of the metal cages required in newer buses had convinced him that whatever pierced the tank probably would have passed between the bars of a cage. `` In this situation, the way this accident occurred, that cage would have had little or no effect,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said in an interview Thursday. The converted school bus owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Radcliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> God </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> burst into flames after being hit head-on by a pickup truck traveling the wrong way on Interstate 71 near <LOCATION> Carrollton </LOCATION> on Saturday night. Twenty-seven of the 67 people on board died of smoke inhalation in one of the nation's deadliest bus crashes. The driver, who was allegedly drunk, has been charged with 27 counts of murder. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Fasone </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> team investigating the crash, said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s findings could prove true. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> team will continue trying to determine whether a cage would have minimized damage to the fuel tank. Although his report will not be complete for several weeks, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the fuel tank probably was punctured by another piece of the bus. In addition to the gash, <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators reported this week that the fuel tank had been pushed back 26 inches and off one of the two straps that fastened it to the bus. A protective cage might have held the tank in place, resulting in an even larger hole, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said.
