<HEAD>Seized Research Vessel Likely To be Returned to Owners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A research vessel that was part of the Titanic exploration, seized under the government's `` zero-tolerance'' policy after a small amount of marijuana was found, will probably be returned to its owners, officials say. Atlantis II was seized here Wednesday after a routine inspection turned up traces of marijuana and two pipes in the shaving kit of one of the ship's 25 crew members, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Thursday. Spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> said it was clear the 210-foot vessel's owners, the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution in <LOCATION> Woods </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, `` were innocent parties They've been extremely cooperative in this matter.'' Crew member <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Buzzards </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, pleaded guilty Thursday to a misdemeanor charge of drug possession, said <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> was sentenced to a year of probation and fined $ 100. The vessel's owners are forwarding a letter to Customs supporting the anti-drug effort and assuring officials they intend to tighten security aboard the ship, <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> said. `` Once we receive their agreement and their letter outlining the procedures they will take, then we fully intend to return the Atlantis II to the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution,'' he said. Atlantis II and its contents, including a three-person research submarine named <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON>, are worth $ 80 million, <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Atlantis </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> Wednesday from <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, where it had stopped for supplies after geological and biological research work near the <LOCATION> Galapagos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, the institution's director of research. The seizure shocked the scientific community at <LOCATION> Woods </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, where the ship is based, said <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>. Construction of Atlantis II and <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> was substantially funded by federal research agencies, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. He noted that the 25-foot <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> is owned by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. Scientists aboard Atlantis II used <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> in 1986 to explore and photograph the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> site where the Titanic lies. The luxury liner went down 74 years ago after striking an iceberg only five days into its maiden voyage. More than 1,500 people died. Scientists found the Titanic in September 1985 on a joint U.S.-French expedition. At least 22 vessels have been seized across the country since the zero-tolerance policy went into effect.
