 A <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> fighter jet crashed just after takeoff today, killing the pilot and damaging a farm building, a military spokesman said. The crash occurred this morning as the Harrier was taking off on a routine training mission, said <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Rhine </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Henatsch </PERSON>. The aircraft plowed into a field about a half-mile from the end of the runway at <LOCATION> Guetersloh </LOCATION> airfield, about 45 miles northeast of Dortmund, he said. Flying debris from the crash damaged a farm building near the site, but there were no injuries on the ground, he said. <PERSON> Henatsch </PERSON> said the name of the pilot was being withheld pending notification of next of kin and an investigation was launched into what caused the crash. There have been several fatal crashes in recent months in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> involving American, British and French military jets.
