<HEAD>Guns, Ammunition Found Inside Temple, 20 More People Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for 1st Ld-Writethru to PM-India-Sikhs, a0466. LEADS
with 12 grafs to UPDATE with tour of temple, higher death toll,
other details. Pick up 8th graf pvs: `Sikh militants...' Edits
thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh militants left Chinese-made AK-47 rifles, grenades and ammunition inside the Golden Temple when they surrendered to police following a 10-day siege, a tour of the shrine showed today. Municipal work crews continued to clean debris from the temple complex, and police reported 20 more people shot to death by Sikh extremists overnight. Five of the victims killed Thursday night were Hindu migrant workers who were lined up against a wall and shot. Reporters taken to the temple found that one of its windows had been shattered during the confrontation between the extremists and police. A bullet hole could be seen in the marble near the entrance to the shrine. The weapons were on the floor above the inner sanctum of the temple, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine. The siege ended Wednesday when the last 46 Sikh extremists holed up inside the temple surrendered to police. The Guru <PERSON> Granth </PERSON> <PERSON> Sahib </PERSON>, the holy book of the Sikhs, lay covered under a cloth in the inner sanctum on the ground floor. There was a burn mark across the cloth, which appeared to have been made by a bullet passing close to its surface. In rooms around the pool surrounding the temple, reporters were shown the militants' supply of tinned butter, wheat and lentils as well as army uniforms the extremists apparently used to impersonate servicemen in some of their raids. In Room No. 48, the office assigned to the militant <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, reporters saw files of threatening letters that had been sent by the group and other militant factions to <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> residents. Some demanded money. In other rooms there were blood-stained clothing, toiletries and medical kits. Police said the migrant workers killed Thursday were lined up against a wall and shot by a gang of eight radicals, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The killings occurred in the village of <PERSON> Chinna </PERSON> <PERSON> Karam </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, about 18 miles northwest of the <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> holy city of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. It was the second attack on migrant workers this week, suggesting that the estremists were trying to undercut the mainstay of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state's economy, which is agriculture. Overnight Tuesday, Sikh gunmen killed more than 30 Hindu workers from <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Orissa </LOCATION> as they slept at a camp near the state capital of <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>. Other deaths reported overnight included six people killed in <LOCATION> Jalandhar </LOCATION> district, six in <LOCATION> Bhatinda </LOCATION> district and three other shot to death in separate incidents around the state. The killings raised to at least 1,108 the number of people killed by Sikh extremists in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since the start of the year. In all of 1987, about 1,030 people died. Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for more political autonomy or an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, where they are a majority. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people and claim they are discriminated against by the nation's majority Hindus State-run <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> today quoted an unidentified government official in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> as saying cleaning was nearly complete at the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> and `` steps are being taken to restore traditional rituals.'' Police cordoned off the complex May 9 after radicals inside fired on police officers conducting an inspection outside its walls, wounding five of them. Rituals at the golden-domed temple include a continuous reading of the Sikh holy book and the singing of hymns. <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION> was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam. Visitors to the inner sanctum of the temple often take a ceremonial dip in the surrounding pool, which is considered sacred.
