<HEAD>Defendant Identified by Voice Found Guilty of Rape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man accused of attacking five women was convicted of rape after the victims identified him as their assailant by listening to his tape-recorded voice. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, 27, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> factory worker, was found guilty Thursday of 31 charges in a 54-count indictment, including four rapes and one attempted rape. The jury, which deliberated for 10 days, deadlocked on 21 charges, including one rape, an attempted rape and robbery. He was acquitted on two burglary charges. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> displayed no emotion when the verdict was announced. His attorney, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Naiburg </PERSON>, conceded during the six-week trial that one man committed all the crimes but contended that police had arrested the wrong man. He said he would appeal the conviction. In most of the incidents, the assailant wore a mask or it was too dark to see his face, the victims testified. According to Prosecutor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahearn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> stalked his victims for days, confronted them in their bedrooms as they slept and put a screwdriver to their throats. Usually, the victims were blond and attractive, ranging in age from 10 to 55. The attacks at homes on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s affluent <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shore </LOCATION> began in January 1983 and ended in February 1987, when <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> was arrested. He faces a maximum of 25 years on each rape conviction, and <PERSON> Ahearn </PERSON> said he would request the maximum on each count to run consecutively. <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Judge <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Namm </PERSON> set sentencing for June 22. Six victims, four of rape and two of attempted rape, picked <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> from a `` voice lineup'' by listening to recordings of his voice and other male voices and identifying his as that of the man who had attacked them. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Puzo </PERSON>, the author of `` The Godfather,'' also testified that his Bay Shore home was burglarized in 1986 and that several pieces of luggage were stolen. Luggage given to <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>'s girlfriend was identified by <PERSON> Puzo </PERSON> as belonging to him. <PERSON> Naiburg </PERSON> pointed to discrepancies in the descriptions victims gave of their assailant's voice. Some said he spoke with a thick <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> accent. At least one recalled the voice of an educated man with no accent. <PERSON> Naiburg </PERSON> directed the bulk of his defense against the `` voice lineup,'' calling it prejudicial and flawed.
