<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A school bus overturned on a sharp curve called `` Devil's Elbow'' and plunged down an embankment in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, injuring 60 people, and another school bus flipped in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, injuring 34 fifth-graders and others Both accidents occurred Thursday afternoon. In the accident about 90 miles north of <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, the bus went off the curve, fell about 20 feet and landed upside down, police said. The bus, carrying 45 children and 15 adult chaperones from the <ORGANIZATION> Walnut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shore </LOCATION>, was returning from a field trip in <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>. Sixteen children and eight adults were treated at <ORGANIZATION> Divine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Providence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Williamsport </LOCATION>, nursing supervisor <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Herz </PERSON> said. An adult passenger and a child were hospitalized in fair condition today, but most of the other injuries were minor. Twenty-nine children and seven adults were treated at two other area hospitals, mostly for bumps, scrapes and bruises, officials said. State police said the driver was unfamiliar with the state road, which he had taken to avoid a traffic tie-up, and said speed may have contributed to the accident. `` He did n't know the turn was there,'' Trooper <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said. In the <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> crash, 63 people escaped serious injury when their bus overturned on a county road south of <LOCATION> Albion </LOCATION>. Thirty-four passengers were treated at hospitals in <LOCATION> Marshalltown </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> for minor lacerations, bruises and fractures, then released, official