<HEAD>Authorities Say Physicians Got Kickbacks in Medicare Fraud Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 1,000 physicans in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> received kickbacks as part of a <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> fraud scheme involving a medical laboratory company, say federal officials. It is believed to be the nation's largest <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> fraud case in terms of the number of doctors involved, said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON>. The 987 doctors were paid a $ 50 kickback by <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diagnostic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for each patient referred to the company for a blood circulation test, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office has mailed letters to 382 of the doctors over the last two days requesting they pay the government three times the amount they allegedly received in order to avoid civil action and expulsion from the Medicare program, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. The 382 doctors received a total of $ 200,000 in fees, or an average of about $ 523. Most of them were calling to offer to settle the claims, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. Many of the remaining doctors received less than $ 150 and are not expected to be pursued in the case, The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> reported today, citing unidentified federal sources. Fewer than 100 physicians received more than $ 5,000 apiece in fees and are expected to be prosecuted individually, the newspaper said. Medical Diagnostic Services billed Medicare $ 400 to $ 1,000 per patient, contending that it had performed a sophisticated test when in fact it had conducted only a simple, routine test, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. `` This is a classic Medicare rip-off,'' one investigator familiar with the case, which is being investigated by the Inspector General's Office of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney's Office in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, told the Inquirer. Between August 1982 and February 1985, <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diagnostic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, operating under four different corporate names in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, billed Medicare for about $ 4.5 million, the newspaper said. In July 1987, the owners of <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diagnostic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cortese </PERSON>, each pleaded guilty to one count of mail fraud in defrauding the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> system and agreed to cooperate with federal prosecutors.
