<HEAD>Art Thieves Steal Three Masterpieces From Dutch Museum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Stolen were...' to CORRECT date of
Carnations.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thieves smashed a window at the Municipal Museum today and made off with three 19th-century paintings worth up to $ 52 million, including works by <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>. Museum officials said it was the largest art theft in modern Dutch history. Stolen were `` Carnations,'' an 1888 work by <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>; `` The House of <LOCATION> Maitre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Billaud </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Nevers </LOCATION>,'' by Dutch painter <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jongkind </PERSON>, from 1874; and `` Bottle with Apples,'' an 1894 still life by <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>, the French impressionist. Museum director <PERSON> Wim </PERSON> <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> estimated their combined value at $ 52 million, but the <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction firm in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> set their worth at $ 11 million. The theft at the downtown museum, also known as the <ORGANIZATION> Stedelijk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, was discovered after 5 a.m. when someone broke a window in the building and triggered an alarm. Museum spokesman <PERSON> Maarten </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertheux </PERSON> said no one was inside at the time. He said the museum's estimated 3,000 works are protected only by an electronic alarm system when the museum is closed. Round-the-clock surveillance by security personnel was abolished as an economy measure in 1975, <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said. `` This is a terrible loss of prestige for -LRB- museum -RRB- security,'' he told reporters. The stolen paintings were not insured. The museum, famed for its collection of works by 19th - and 20th-century masters, is a three-story building with large windows on the street level The thieves entered through one of those windows that faces a secluded, tree-shrouded area, officials said. They walked through five galleries before reaching the room where the stolen paintings were on display with two other <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> works, according to deputy director <PERSON> Rini </PERSON> <PERSON> Dippel </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Dippel </PERSON> speculated that the thieves left the other two <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> paintings, `` The Rocking Chair'' and `` The Diggers,'' because they were substantially larger than `` Carnations,'' which measures 18.4 by 15 inches. There were conflicting accounts on how the theft was discovered. Police spokeswoman <PERSON> Heleen </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Weijden </PERSON> police arrived on the scene after the alarm sounded and entered the museum but failed to notice the theft. She said the theft was discovered an hour later by a private security guard. <PERSON> Bertheux </PERSON> said museum staffers and police discovered the theft about 20 minutes after the alarm sounded. Recent tests of the alarm system showed it took only three minutes for police and guards to get there, <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said. He could give no explanation for the delay. Mrs. <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Weijden </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Interpol </ORGANIZATION> and customs services around the world were alerted. The Municipal Museum is next to the <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gogh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, which has the world's largest collection by the Dutch master. About 200 yards from the two museums is the Rijksmuseum, the nation's largest repository of works by <PERSON> Rembrandt </PERSON>. According to <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s, the stolen <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> is worth $ 1.6 million to $ 2.1 million; the <ORGANIZATION> Cezanne </ORGANIZATION>, $ 7.9 million; and the Jongkind, $ 147,000. Ms. <PERSON> Dippel </PERSON> said those estimates were based on black and white photographs in a museum catalog. <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said he based his higher estimate on the fact that `` there is a <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> involved, and recent price developments -LRB- for <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Goghs </PERSON> -RRB- have been dramatic.'' In March 1987, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Sunflowers'' drew $ 39.8 million at a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> auction. In November, an unidentified collector paid $ 53 million for the Dutch painter's `` Irises'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> speculated that the theft may have been commissioned by a private art collector, since the paintings are too famous to be sold on the public market. `` I've got the impression that they chose the paintings with a clear purpose in mind,'' he said. `` This'll go straight to somebody's room or home, I guess.''
