<HEAD>Tribal Chief Who Remembered Arrival of White Settlers Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tribal chief who witnessed the arrival of some of the first white settlers a century ago has died at age 109, it was reported Friday. Chief <PERSON> Wavela </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazetese </PERSON>, from the <LOCATION> Mwenezi </LOCATION> district of <LOCATION> Matabeleland </LOCATION> province in western <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, died in his village Sunday after a short illness, the state-owned Chronicle newspaper said. Mazetese, in a 1984 newspaper interview, said he was a boy tending his father's cattle when the first whites he had seen appeared on horses and in wagons led by oxen. Historians said the whites were probably among the first settlers to arrive in the former British colony of <LOCATION> Rhodesia </LOCATION> in the 1890s. The colony won its independence as a black-governed nation in 1980 following a guerrilla war. It was renamed <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, after an ancient gold-rich African kingdom. Mazetese is survived by a wife and 20 children.
