<HEAD>Seals Dying of Mysterious Pneumonia Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of seals in Danish waters are dying of pneumonia, and the mysterious epidemic could spread to marine mammals in the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, a biologist said Friday. More than 200 harp seals are known to have died in recent weeks on the island of <PERSON> Anholt </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kattegat </LOCATION> strait between <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, said biologist <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mortensen </PERSON>. He said the area's entire 1988 generation of seals was lost because their sick mothers aborted. Dying or dead seals also have been found beached on the islands of <LOCATION> Laesoe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hesseloe </PERSON> and as far south as the port city of <LOCATION> Helsingoer </LOCATION>, giving rise to fears that the infection might spead, he said. He said the virus spreads by direct contact between adult seals as they lie close together on land, adding that it resembles an influenza that struck hundreds of seals on the Canadian and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> eastern coasts in 1980. Another expert, <PERSON> Knud </PERSON> <PERSON> Pedersen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterinary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Serum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said he suspected a herpes-like virus similar to one blamed for seal deaths of seals off <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> a few years ago. Experts from several government agencies met in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION> to discuss the crisis. They agreed that more seals will die in the next few months as the epidemic spreads. The harp seal was near extinction in 1975, when it was declared a protected species. An estimated 5,000 of the mammals inhabit Danish waters, breeding 500 to 1,000 pups a year.
