<HEAD>Young Men Killed in Blast Portrayed as Pious, But Misled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Kuwaiti men killed when their bomb-laden car blew up before reaching its intended target were pious Moslems who were duped by criminals, it was reported Friday. The newspaper Al-Qabas also said that fighting terrorism should include `` immunizing citizens against falling easy prey to protagonists of crime and deepening sentiments of patriotism with the youth.'' The paper warned that more terrrorism should be expected. <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said the two men were planning to park the car in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> building in downtown <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> on Wednesday, but the explosives apparently went off prematurely. The blast was the third in this northern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> country in less than a month. In December 1983, a car bomb exploded at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French embassies, and in 1985, an attempt was made on the life of the emir, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sabah </PERSON>. Last month, a <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jetliner was hijacked for 16 days and two Kuwaitis aboard were killed by the gunmen, who have been described as pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem fundamentalists. `` We have to shoulder our historic responsibility ... because confining our attitude to condemation of crimes and counting casualties will be without avail if we want our country to live in peace and security,'' <PERSON> Al-Qabas </PERSON> said. The two young <PERSON> Kuwaitis </PERSON>, who have been identified as <PERSON> Nasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, 22, and <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdel-Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Mousa </PERSON>, 23, were killed when the car they were traveling in exploded near the airline's head office. Al-Qabas quoted a sister of <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> as saying that her family was surprised to learn about the incident. She described her brother as `` a fervent Moslem who strictly performs his religious obligations and leads a normal life. We did not discern anything abnormal in his day-to-day behavior.'' She said he was a teacher at an elementary school, unmarried and owned the car that exploded. Her family did not know the companion killed with him, she said. Al-Qabas said <PERSON> Al-Mousa </PERSON> was a geography student at <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and was married with no children. The paper quoted <PERSON> Al-Mousa </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Adnan </PERSON>, as saying his brother was `` a very committed Moslem.'' His brother recently traveled to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, he said.
