<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Airport Bjt   05-20 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Airport, Bjt,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Narita Airport Still Source Of Tension A Decade Later</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NARITA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years after its opening, <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> is still surrounded by barbed wire and riot police _ bitter reminders of the often violent war between disaffected farmers and the government. Now an ambitious expansion plan threatens to bring more trouble. Since its conception 22 years ago, farmers and demonstrators have clashed ferociously with riot police over plans to expropriate vast amounts of fertile farmland and polish it into a gleaming international gateway. Today, the sprawling <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, located 40 miles from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, resembles a beseiged city, patrolled day and night by 700 policeman. Departing passengers and guests are frisked with metal detectors at several security checkpoints and at times required to produce identification when entering the airport grounds. Six lives have been lost in bloody battles since the 1966 government decision designated <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> as the site for a new airport. But <PERSON> Koji </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitahara </PERSON>, leader of a group of airport opponents, claims the figures mean nothing. `` More lives will be taken in the fight,'' he vows. Together with the Chukaku-ha, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest radical group, anti-Narita protesters have sabotaged construction work and even managed several times to delay the airport inauguration, originally scheduled for March 1971. In one such clash, a handful of leftists crept into <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION>'s 16th-floor control tower through a sewer tunnel and destroyed its radar, weather and communications equipment Outside, about 6,000 demonstrators fought pitched battles with 13,000 policemen. The sabotage pushed back the opening for another two months and it was not until May 20, 1978, that the first flight took off from the heavily guarded <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION>. `` For 22 years we have fought the government for disrupting our lives and taking away our right to a normal livelihood,'' said <PERSON> Kitahara </PERSON>, 66. `` If we allow the completion of the second-phase construction project, we will have no future,'' he said in an interview at his home 500 yards from <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION>'s only runway. Overhead, a jet roared by. <PERSON> Kitahara </PERSON>, who has been arrested three times in his fight against the airport, said many of the displaced farmers have been reduced to working as day laborers on construction sites. Some wives have taken up part-time jobs and `` a few of the men even work as guards at the airport'' to make ends meet, he added. `` But many of them come to me now and say they wished they never sold their land,'' <PERSON> Kitahara </PERSON> said. `` They're no longer their own boss. They have to take orders from someone else.'' Government plans call for <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> to be doubled in size by March 1991 with the construction of two runways measuring 8,250 feet and 10,560 feet, and a second terminal building to increase the current capacity of 11 million passengers annually to 23 million. But like the first stage, construction for the expansion has encountered strong opposition and plans originally targeted for completion in 1974 have only reached the ground-breaking stage. A protest rally has been scheduled for Sunday. According to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, eight families are thwarting the expansion by refusing to give up 52.6-acres of farmland. `` We hope to come to terms with them through talks,'' said <PERSON> Masataka </PERSON> <PERSON> Takemoto </PERSON>, chief of public relations at the airport authority office. He said about 325 families have been resettled in nearby farmlands since 1966 after agreeing to cede their properties. <PERSON> Takemoto </PERSON> claims about 200 members of the Marxist Chukaku-ha, or <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Core </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, live around the airport and are threatening to harm the farmers if they sell their land. They maintain the airport may be used for military purposes. `` Even if the farmers want to sell, they ca n't because of fear of what the Chukaku-ha will do,'' he said. Known for violent tactics and using homemade projectiles and flamethrowers, the radical group has spearheaded the anti-Narita movement. It was blamed for forcing the temporary closure of <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> for one hour in 1985 after firebombs were hurled on the runway. `` The group has taken up the matter as just another way of rebelling against the government,'' said <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamo </PERSON>, deputy chief of public relations of the airport authority. `` As soon as they find some other anti-government cause to support, they'll latch onto it. Despite the protests, initial work on the second runway has begun, tightly cordoned off by coils of barbed wire and guarded closely by riot police. Should the farmers refuse to sell their holdings, <PERSON> Takemoto </PERSON> added, `` we will take the land through legal means.'' `` We will finish the airport,'' <PERSON> Takemoto </PERSON> said. `` As a major power in the world, we have an obligation to complete the construction.''
</TEXT>
