nt hall were standing on their seats to miss nothing of the hair-raising duel <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> initially weathered the onslaught, capturing a second piece and countering with a mating threat of his own. But problems arose as he ran into time trouble. On the 25th move, he missed a chance to win in one move. On the 39th, he exceeded the time limit where he was one move short of the control in a position that the experts afterwards said was probably a draw. Against <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>'s <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiel </PERSON> in Thursday's sixth round, <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> was his old self again, coolly making the most of his slim advantage in a Queen's Indian, gradually increasing the pressure against black's weakened center and clinching victory on the 39th move. <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>'s encounter with Dutchman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Timman </PERSON>, ranked third on the world rating list, was more of an anticlimax. The world champion, playing white, refrained from taking the initiative against his theoretically weaker opponent. Visiting grandmaster <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> hypothesized that <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> was still `` somewhat dizzy'' from his victory over <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>. Early on, <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> had some trouble in stopping white's attack, but eventually evened out around his 40th to sign the peace five moves later. The tournament, with a <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> category 17 and an average rating of 2,674 points _ the strongest ever held _ will continue Sunday with <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> facing <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> playing <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> in seventh-round action. After six rounds, <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> had 4 points; <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> 3 -LCB-; <PERS