<HEAD>`Pinging' Piano Alerts Owner To Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LENOIR, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pop of a burning piano's strings was sweet music to its owner, who credits the noise with awakening him in time to escape a fire that destroyed his home. `` I was awakened by a ping, ping, ping,'' said <PERSON> Bennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>, 41. `` It sounded like someone playing it, but it was a high, shrill sound.'' Thursday's fire, apparently sparked by a faulty electrical heater in the basement, quickly enveloped the two-story wood house in this western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> town, fire officials said. <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>'s wife and a son had already left for work and school when the fire spread and the sound of the piano woke <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>. Flames caused the piano's strings to snap, creating the `` pinging'' sound. <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> said he opened his eyes to see smoke curling under the door of the bedroom. He grabbed his clothes and made his way through thick, black smoke to the front door, he said. <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> said he and his wife bought the piano for their younger son to practice on. An older son no longer lives at home. `` I'm just thankful we had the piano,'' <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> said. `` I'm not sure I would have awoke if it had n't been for it.''
