<HEAD>Network Seeking To Stop State From Enforcing Ban on Exit Polls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILLINGS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> is seeking an injunction against the state of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to keep it from enforcing its prohibition on exit polls, used by the media to forecast the winners of elections. <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> law forbids anyone to question voters about their choices within 200 feet of a polling place. Violations are misdemeanors punishable by up to six months in jail and a fine of $ 500. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> maintains the law violates its First Amendment rights of free speech and commentary on the electoral process. The ban interferes with the gathering and reporting of truthful and significant information about the political process on election day, the network argued in federal court papers. `` Carried to its logical extreme, two neighbors coming out of a polling place after voting could not ask how the other voted,'' said Billings attorney <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who is representing <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. `` Those who seek accurate, legitimate information can not do so.'' The lawsuit, filed Thursday, asks for preliminary and permanent injunctions to stop the state from enforcing the 200-foot prohibition. Defendants in the suit are Attorney General <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Greely </PERSON> and Commissioner of Political Practices <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Colburg </PERSON>. Both <PERSON> Colburg </PERSON> and Greely were out of their offices today and unavailable for comment. The 1985 law was an outgrowth of the 1980 presidential election, when the major TV networks declared <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the winner before polls had closed in the Mountain and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> time zones. The restriction was sought so that voters in the West would not be discouraged from voting because the election was already declared over by the media.
