<HEAD>Women and Children First _ Into Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fourteen-year-old <PERSON> Niveen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahman </PERSON> does the housework for her family now that her mother is in jail. She cooks and cleans, and when clashes with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers erupt, she runs to the streets to help youngsters choking on tear gas. `` I am doing the same as my mother. It's my duty,'' said <PERSON> Niveen </PERSON>, sitting in her family's cement block house in the Shati refugee camp. In the next room was a box full of chickens that the family is raising to eat as the Arab uprising persists, bringing with it worsening economic conditions. A new role for Moslem children and women, both held under strict rule in the traditional religious society, is one of the changes spawned by the nearly six-month rebellion against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s occupation of the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> According to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures through April, a quarter of the 4,344 Palestinians in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> injured in the revolt were under 16. Israeli authorities complain that their soldiers are increasingly facing women and children rioters. `` Now we are the leaders,'' said 19-year-old <LOCATION> Rafat </LOCATION>, sitting on the floor of another cement block house down the street from <PERSON> Niveen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahman </PERSON>'s home. `` Youth are leading, burning tires, stoning soldiers,'' said <PERSON> Rafat </PERSON>, who would not give his last name. `` Women try to help the boys who are arrested or try to stop arrests. They go to the kids when soldiers throw tear gas.'' <PERSON> Niveen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dahman </PERSON>'s mother, <LOCATION> Widad </LOCATION>, was arrested this month as an `` inciter'' along with two other women in Shati. They were the first women to be jailed in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> under administrative detention laws, where no trials or specific charges are required. Each was given six months in prison. Palestinian activitist <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Khas </PERSON> says the arrests showed that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has recognized the new power of women in the uprising. Women, allowed out during curfew, became messengers and lookouts, she said. `` Women found their authority and strength and started organizing,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Khas </PERSON>, who runs a kindergarten program throughout the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. As for Palestinian youth, Ms. <PERSON> Khas </PERSON> said, `` They did what youngsters do _ try to change things. It was a spontaneous mass revolt.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and fundamentalist Moslem groups are behind the rebellion, but Ms. <PERSON> Khas </PERSON> said it was the young, `` the grassroots leadership,'' that kept the uprising going. She pointed out that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had arrested many traditional leaders active in PLO-organized committees of lawyers, doctors and other professionals, but still the revolt persists. `` They're all the time arresting what they call the leadership, but they have n't gotten the leaders,'' she said. <PERSON> Riad </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Agha </PERSON>, a former president of <ORGANIZATION> Gaza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said the stifling life of the refugee camps has spawned young leaders who do not have their parents' fear of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers. `` The uprising right now is led by youth age 15 to 25. Most live in the refugee camps around the strip and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` They will never listen to the older generation.'' <PERSON> Agha </PERSON> described the revolt this way: `` Most of the men go to work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and leave their sons at home to throw stones.'' He said sons sometimes stop fathers from going to work, but not forever. <PERSON> Agha </PERSON>, who has a Ph.D. from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION>, said many of the youth in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> have taken up the hard-line ideas of the Islamic Jihad, or Holy War, a radical fundamentalist group that wants an Islamic state including all of what is now <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. He said if the revolt persists with no Israeli concessions, youth will emerge as political leaders and replace so-called moderates who would be satisfied with a Palestinian state alongside <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The young men on the streets think they are winning, since they have faced <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s might with only rocks and painted slogans. One day last week, a group of boys and young men set a tire ablaze at the entrance to <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. They were waiting by the road with stones in hand. <PERSON> Hamad </PERSON>, who said he was 15 but looked years younger, said they wanted revenge for Arabs beaten earlier, and they hoped <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers would come by. They also were targeting cars taking workers to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he said. `` I do n't go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hamad </PERSON> said. `` My work is here _ throwing stones.''
