<HEAD>New Study: Another Great Quake Unlikely Soon In San Francisco</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cambodians-Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Devastating earthquakes have occurred only every 200 to 400 years on the northern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fault </LOCATION>, says a study that provides some comfort for <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Franciscans </LOCATION> worried about a repeat of the deadly 1906 quake. <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> geologist <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Prentice </PERSON>, who presented her study of earthquake frequency Friday at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geophysical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>'s spring meeting in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, said she found evidence of six great quakes in the last 2,000 years along a 260-mile stretch of the fault. The last was the 1906 shaker that killed at least 2,500 people. At this interval, it would mean that the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area is unlikely to have a devastating quake within the next 100 years and possiby much longer, said <PERSON> Prentice </PERSON>'s professor and co-author, geologist <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sieh </PERSON>. However, <PERSON> Sieh </PERSON> cautioned the study is preliminary, so while `` one is tempted to conclude -LRB- with certainty -RRB- that a great earthquake is not likely in the near future in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, that would be a premature conclusion at this point.'' The study involved only the northern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION>. The Hayward Fault and other faults in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> also pose a threat, and the state <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> says the probability of a damaging earthquake in the <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area in the next 30 years is about 50 percent. So `` people should n't get too complacent'' because of the new study, <PERSON> Prentice </PERSON> said Thursday in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Prentice </PERSON> made excavations across the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arena </LOCATION> about 160 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and found evidence of at least six large quakes in the last 2,000 years, suggesting an occurrence of every 300 to 400 years. However, the study also found evidence the fault is building up strain at a rate that suggests the interval between large quakes might be only 200 years, <PERSON> Sieh </PERSON> said. The 1906 quake ruptured a stretch of fault that starts just south of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mendocino </LOCATION>, then runs south through <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Marin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bautista </LOCATION>. Federal emergency officials have estimated a repeat of the quake would kill up to 11,000 people, seriously injure up to 44,000 and cause $ 38 billion in damage. For <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, forecasts of a great quake's advent are grimmer. Based on other studies, including work by <PERSON> Sieh </PERSON>, the state <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> says another major devastating quake in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> is more than 50 percent likely within the next 25 years. Federal officials have projected that a great quake on the southern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> would kill up to 14,000 people, injure up to 55,000 and cause $ 17 billion in damage. <PERSON> Sieh </PERSON>'s research on the southern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fault </LOCATION> suggests great quakes occur an average of every 140 years on the section from <LOCATION> Tejon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION>, northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Cajon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>. The last such quake occurred in 1857. He also found the next segment to the southeast, from <LOCATION> Cajon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Salton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, breaks in a great or major quake an average of every 200 to 250 years, with the last such quake more than 300 years ago, suggesting the segment is overdue for a big quake.
