<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prostitute arrested on charges of attempted manslaughter for selling sex while carrying AIDS has been sent home because of her failing health. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherouse </PERSON>, 24, was released from jail and placed under house arrest. Ms. <PERSON> Sherouse </PERSON> was arrested five months ago after investigators said she twice had sex with men knowing she carried the deadly virus. The charges were later dismissed for lack of evidence, but she remained in jail while the prosecution appealed the dismissal. On Thursday, Circuit Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Cycmanick </PERSON> reduced her bail from $ 14,000 to $ 1,000 because of her declining health and a doctor's prognosis that she had less than three years to live. `` There is no way this girl will physically be able to get on the streets again,'' her attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheaffer </PERSON>, said at the hearing. `` I believe her last days should be spent with some degree of dignity. We should n't allow her to die like we would n't allow some animals to die.'' The AIDS virus triggered severe infections in most of her vital organs last month, said her doctor, <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>. She had surgery, a seizure and almost died twice of heart failure, he said. `` I feel real great about going home,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Sherouse </PERSON>, frail but smiling as she left the <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jail </ORGANIZATION>. She was steadied by her attorney. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> wrote the judge that he counseled Ms. <PERSON> Sherouse </PERSON> about the possibilities of transmitting the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus through sex, but added, `` The ability to understand the gravity of the situation was found to be uninterpretable by the patient.'' Prosecutor <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogle </PERSON> argued that her release c