<HEAD>Reagan Assures Cuban-Americans Freedom in Cuba Is `Non-Negotiable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told a cheering audience of Cuban-Americans on Friday that he considers the freedom of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> `` a non-negotiable issue.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> spoke to a small gathering in the White House Roosevelt Room at a ceremony marking the 86th anniversary of the establishment of the Cuban republic. The walls of the room are adorned with pictures and other memorabilia of <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, who led a detachment of volunteer cavalry known as the Rough Riders in action in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> during the Spanish-American war in 1898. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stood by the president's side as he spoke. The audience frequently interrupted, standing to applaud and cry out `` bravo.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ended his speech `` Viva <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> libre,'' or `` Long live free <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.'' `` Cuban-Americans have demonstrated that free people can come together unencumbered by tyranny, and I am confident the time will come when the spirit of freedom will reign in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> itself,'' he said. `` Having suffered personally the evils of communism, you have an acute understanding of the danger that communist expansion poses to this hemisphere,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told the Cuban-Americans. `` You have stood in support of people everywhere who seek freedom, such as the people of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' `` Let me assure you, as far as this administration is concerned, the freedom of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is a non-negotiable issue.'' `` We will never, ever negotiate away the dream of every Cuban-American, a dream that I too hold in my heart, that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> will again join the family of free and democratic nations,'' the president said. `` Only 90 miles of ocean separate the island of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but between our governments is an unbridgeable gulf.''
