<HEAD>Van Gogh, Cezanne Paintings Stolen in Biggest-Ever Dutch Art Theft</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos AMS1, AMS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Art thieves smashed a window in the Municipal Museum early Friday and stole three masterpieces worth up to $ 52 million, including works by <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>. It was the biggest art theft in Dutch history. The burglars broke a ground-floor window before dawn in the museum's north wing, which is relatively sheltered from public view, said museum spokesman <PERSON> Maarten </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertheux </PERSON>. The thieves then walked through five galleries to reach the room where the works were hanging, he said. Stolen were `` Carnations,'' an 1888 work by the Dutch painter <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>; `` Bottle with Apples,'' a still life painted in 1894 by the French master <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>; and `` The House of <PERSON> Maitre </PERSON> <PERSON> Billaud </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Nevers </LOCATION>,'' an 1874 painting by Dutch artist <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jongkind </PERSON>. Two other valuable <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> paintings, `` The Diggers'' and `` The Rocking Chair,'' were hanging in the same gallery but were not taken. <PERSON> Rini </PERSON> <PERSON> Dippel </PERSON>, the museum's deputy director, said they may have been left because they are substantially larger than the others. Museum director <PERSON> Wim </PERSON> <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said the stolen paintings are worth an estimated $ 52 million, although experts from <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction house in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> estimated their worth at $ 11 million. The Municipal Museum houses a collection of about 3,000 works from the 19th and 20th centuries and is next door to the <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gogh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, which has 220 paintings by the Dutch master, the world's largest collection Beeren and other art experts speculated that the theft was commissioned by a private art collector, since the <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON> are too famous to be sold publicly and since the other <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> works were n't taken. `` I've got the impression that they chose the paintings with a clear purpose in mind,'' <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said. `` This'll go straight to somebody's room or home.'' `` There's a very good reporting system -LRB- on art thefts -RRB- these days ... If they're offered for sale at a bona fide art dealer or auction house, that'll be known right away,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Leeman </PERSON> of the Van Gogh Museum. <PERSON> Bertheux </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that there was no one in the museum at the time of the burglary. Around-the-clock surveillance by security personnel was abolished in 1975 to save money. Authorities were alerted when an alarm went off about 5 a.m., but there were conflicting accounts on when the theft was discovered. Police spokesman <PERSON> Joost </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijngaarden </PERSON> said police arrived at 5:10 a.m., entered the museum through the broken window and `` found nothing missing.'' He said officers then left the museum and that private security guards discovered the theft about 90 minutes later. But <PERSON> Bertheux </PERSON> said museum officials discovered the theft almost immediately when they entered the building's main lobby and ran past the targeted gallery on their way to investigate the broken window. `` This is a terrible loss of prestige for -LRB- museum -RRB- security,'' <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> told reporters at an impromptu news conference. He appeared shaken and pale. The paintings were not insured against theft. <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said he based his loss estimate on the fact that `` there is a <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> involved, and recent price developments -LRB- for <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Goghs </PERSON> -RRB- have been dramatic.'' In March 1987, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Sunflowers'' fetched $ 39.8 million at a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> auction. In November, an unidentified collector paid $ 53 million for <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Irises'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Dippel </PERSON> said experts from <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s based their estimate on black and white photographs of the paintings in a museum catalog. According to <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s, the <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> is worth $ 1.6 million to $ 2.1 million; the <ORGANIZATION> Cezanne </ORGANIZATION> is worth $ 7.9 million; and the Jongkind is worth $ 147,000. The nation's last major art theft was in February 1987, when nine pieces, including works by French painter <PERSON> Jean-Auguste </PERSON> <PERSON> Renoir </PERSON> and Dutch master <PERSON> Pieter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruegel </PERSON>, vanished from an art gallery in the southern city of <LOCATION> Maastricht </LOCATION>. The loss was estimated at $ 2.65 million. The paintings were never recovered.
