<HEAD>Sikh Hideouts Raided After More Deaths Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with 5 more dead; SUBS 11th graf
pvs, ``Five more ...'' with curfew in Pathankot; SUBS 19th graf,
``The latest ...'' with 1 graf to UPDATE figure.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of paramilitary troops and police fanned out across <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state Friday and raided <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> hideouts after reports that militant Sikhs murdered 43 people in an overnight crime spree. Police said a security red alert was issued in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, where Sikhs have allegedly murdered 195 people since May 9, when a government hold on the Sikhs' Golden Temple began. The siege of the holy shrine ended Wednesday with the surrender of the last of the militants holed up inside. At least 42 people, mainly Sikh militants, were killed during the 10-day standoff. Reporters were taken to the temple Friday for the first time since the siege and saw bloodstains, bullet marks, and arms and ammunition. The temple complex, normally visited by 10,000 pilgrims a day, looked shabby and deserted. A stench came from canisters used by the radicals as toilets during the siege. The Guru <PERSON> Granth </PERSON> <PERSON> Sahib </PERSON>, the holy book of the Sikhs, lay under a cloth on the floor. There was a burn mark across the cloth that appeared to have been made by a bullet passing close to its surface. At least 43 people were killed in seven separate attacks in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> late Thursday and Friday, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. Five of the victims killed Thursday night were Hindu migrant workers from the eastern Indian state of <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION>, who were lined up against a wall and shot, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. It was the second attack on migrant workers this week, suggesting that the extremists were trying to undercut the mainstay of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state's economy, which is agriculture. Other victims Thursday night included six killed in <LOCATION> Jalandhar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, six killed in <LOCATION> Bhatinda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, and three people were shot to death in separate incidents around the state. On Friday, five people were killed in a bomb attack on a bus near the town of <LOCATION> Pathankot </LOCATION>, 90 miles north of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. Police imposed a curfew in <LOCATION> Pathankot </LOCATION> after 10 others were killed in separate bomb attacks, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. Eight other deaths occured in <LOCATION> Gurdaspur </LOCATION> district on Friday. `` We fear Sikh terrorists will start a new wave of violence, in fact they are already on a killing spree,'' the director general of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> police, K.P.S. <PERSON> Gill </PERSON>, told reporters in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>. He said police were put on extended hours and were under order to arrest and interrogate any suspect. <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said police imposed a curfew on <LOCATION> Pathankot </LOCATION>. `` Time has come to hit the terrorists with iron fist, and this is what we are going to do,'' he said. At least 9,000 police and paramilitary troops raided suspected hideouts of Sikh radicals in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gurdashpur </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jalandhar </LOCATION> districts, a police officer told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He spoke on condition of anonymity. The districts are considered strongholds of Sikh militants, who have been fighting since 1982 for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. The Golden Temple, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine, has become a base for guerrillas waging the war. <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said authorities recovered 44 weapons, including Chinese-made AK-47 rifles, light machine guns, grenades and 4,900 rounds of ammunition from inside the temple Friday. He said police also found $ 340,000 in Indian currency. The latest killings raised to at least 1,131 the number of people murdered by <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> extremists in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> this year. In all of 1987, about 1,030 people died. Sikhs, whose religion was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam, claim they are discriminated against by Hindus. Sikhs are a minority in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> but comprise a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
