<HEAD>Police Say Teens Who Stole Blasting Caps Planned to Blow Up
Bridges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three teen-agers arrested late last week had planned to blow up <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> bridges using 2,400 stolen blasting caps, police said Friday. `` The kids who stole the dynamite caps were telling other kids about it and they made comments about their plans to blow up bridges,'' <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's Lt. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sample </PERSON> said. `` I did n't take it as a joke at the time. And they certainly did n't tell us it was a joke during interrogation. Police arrested <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Gayton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Caho </PERSON>, all 17, in the May 9 theft of 2,400 explosive blasting caps. The caps are owned by a mining equipment and supply company. Some are fused caps, which are extremely sensitive to shock, and others are electric caps that can be detonated by radio transmissions, police said. The suspects were jailed on felony burglary and theft charges. Their bond ranges from $ 5,000 to $ 10,000. In an interview from jail, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Peoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> he was joking when he told friends he might blow up a bridge. `` Most of the things we did were just spur-of-the-moment ideas,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. He added he planned to sell the caps. Sample said it's unclear whether the blasting caps would have been powerful enough to blow up the highway bridges. `` The experts ... said that if you take 1,000 caps and put them together, you can make a 10-foot crater in the ground,'' Sample said. `` Whether they would hurt a steel bridge, we do n't know.'' He said all but about 60 of the stolen caps have been recovered.
