<HEAD>Armenians Demand Trials Be Opened To Observers And TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Demonstrators converged on the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> building Friday to demand that the trials of those charged in ethnic rioting that killed 32 people be opened to television cameras and Armenian observers. An Armenian activist said in a telephone interview from the republic's capital, <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, that the city was quiet after two large public gatherings earlier in the week. The demonstration by about 30 Armenians across the street from the downtown <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> building indicated continuing skepticism about the prosecution of those suspected of involvement in three days of ethnic rioting that began Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>. Twenty-six Armenians and six Azerbaijanis were killed in the violence, which was touched off by a dispute between the two southern Soviet republics over control of the mountainous <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Most residents of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> are ethnic Armenians, and they began agitating in February to be annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. That touched off large demonstrations in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> in support of their demand. Uniformed and plainclothes police lined the sidewalk in front of the six-story <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, but did not interfere with the protest. Armenian painter <PERSON> Koryun </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagapityan </PERSON>, 60, said he would present a declaration to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> from unions representing Armenian artists, writers and other creative workers calling for `` full openness'' in criminal proceedings against more than 80 people charged in the rioting. Nagapityan read the declaration demandin