State Dept. comment. Picks up 11th graf pvs, ``National police
...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radical students on Friday scaled the walls of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, tossed homemade bombs at its buildings and shouted `` Yankee go home!'' in protests called to mark a bloody demonstration eight years ago. Witnesses said two people were injured in the attack which broke out shortly before noon. Seven attackers were arrested. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> officials said the bombs did n't damage the buildings and no Americans were hurt. Witnesses said students, some of them armed with steel bars, hurled six homemade bombs at police and over the embassy walls topped with barbed wires. Four of the devices, made from crude chemical explosives packed in soft drink cans, exploded with big bangs, sending about 100 people waiting for visa applications running for cover, witnesses said. A police officer was hospitalized with blast wounds on his neck and hands, they said. A student was also injured when he was hit by a policeman armed with an iron bar. Five students carrying one South Korean and two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flags climbed over the 6-foot-high fence and ran around the embassy compound for several minutes, scattering leaflets. One student draped a South Korean national flag over his shoulder while other students tried to destroy two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flags before being overpowered by police, the witnesses said. The students also tried to unfurl a placard which read, `` Drive out <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, culprit of the <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> massacre,'' they said. The placard refered to an anti-government uprising in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> on May 18, 1980, during which hundreds were killed. Friday's protests and others earlier this week were called to commemorate the bloodshed in that southern city. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the embassy incident lasted only about five minutes. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said five policemen and one student were injured. He added, `` There's no excuse for this kind of behavior. There is a political system now in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> that provides for the expression of political views and participation in the political process.'' National police remained on full alert to cope with the demonstrations. Radical groups called for another march in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Saturday to denounce the government. Opposition church groups also called for peaceful protests. In other parts of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and two provincial cities, hundreds of students staged demonstrations and marches, demanding the fall of the government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo and the withdrawal of 41,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stationed here under a mutual defense treaty. Many of the protests were peaceful but some turned into battles with riot police who retaliated with tear gas. In <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, 400 students clashed with police, hurling firebombs and rocks. Eight students were arrested in <LOCATION> Suwon </LOCATION>, 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, when they stormed an office of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with firebombs and sticks. Riot police overpowered the attackers. Protesters have denounced the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in demonstrations this week, charging that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> supports military dictatorship in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Demonstrators broke windows and hurled firebombs Thursday at the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> office of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The center was seized by radicals in February who exploded several bombs that caused minor damage. Radical groups call for the overthrow of the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government which they consider a continuation of its predecessor `` military dictatorship'' led by former President <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> is distrusted by many Koreans because of the role he played in <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>'s government. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> narrowly won presidential elections in December after two opposition candidates ran and split the opposition ticket. On Friday, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s government and the opposition failed to break a stalemate over clearing the way for talks between the president and opposition leaders. Both sides have called for negotiations between the two camps after last month's legislative elections in which the opposition took control of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. Officials of the rival parties have met several times during the past week, but failed to work out details on opening the assembly. One major stumbling block has been <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s plan to include the head of his <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the summit with <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dae-jung </PERSON> and the two other main opposition party leaders, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Young-sam </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong-pil </PERSON>. The opposition leaders want only <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> to meet with the opposition chiefs. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> used to include the chairman of his ruling party in summits, but opposition leaders, emboldened by their election victory last month, now object to the idea.
