 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is about to get a taste of Cajun-style diplomacy as chef <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> carries his fiery recipes abroad and artist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> introduces a new audience to his haunting portraits of <LOCATION> Acadiana </LOCATION>. The two left <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Friday for a 10-day trip to the <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION> that will overlap summit talks between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Seeds for the trip were planted in August, according to <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON>, when a Soviet delegation of scientists and public officials visited <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>'s restaurant, <PERSON> Lafitte </PERSON>'s Landing, in <LOCATION> Donaldsonville </LOCATION>. It was, <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> said, the delegation's first glimpse of rural culture in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` This was not part of their typical American concept. We were the people living off the land,'' the artist said in a telephone interview as he prepared for his departure. The Soviets met <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> and sampled his food. `` I doubt the Soviets ever ate a better meal,'' <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> said later. The Soviets also met <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> and saw his art. `` I told them I paint the people of the land,'' he said. <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON>'s portraits of Acadians, often posed against the backdrop of moss-draped oak trees on bayou shores, captured the imagination of the Soviets. Soviet officials commissioned a <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> portrait and <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> painted him in a yellow suit `` because yellow is a color of peace.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is depicted in front of the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, with a bright sun shining and smaller figures of himself as a child, standing with his parents, in the background. The <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> portrait, and one of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, will make the trip to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, along with about 20 <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> paintings depicting Cajun life. `` I tried to pick things that were kind of universal, one is a horse race, one is a story of a church in the aftermath of a hurricane, one is of a dog, my dog ... one is my little boy with the saying ` Kiss me, I'm Cajun' on his T-shirt,'' said the artist. <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> credits <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> with arranging the trip. <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> got help from the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> congressional delegation. Earlier this week, he said he had raised more than half the $ 130,000 he needed to cover the costs of food and expenses. He said, he wo n't keep any of the money, however. `` The Soviets will keep every nickel of revenue,'' he said. `` I hope <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> makes a better deal than I did.'' <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> said he hopes both world leaders will visit the temporary <LOCATION> Cajun </LOCATION> restaurant, <PERSON> Lafitte </PERSON>'s Landing East, where he and <PERSON> Folse </PERSON> will display their artistry. `` We're pretty sure about <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> -LRB- paying a visit to the restaurant -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Rodrigue </PERSON> said. `` The president, we do n't know.''
