<FIRST>u w AM-StarWarsReport     05-20 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Star Wars Report,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advisory Panel Calls for Slower Star Wars Deployment Schedule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> should take a slower, more measured approach to the deployment of a Star Wars anti-missile defense system, a scientific advisory panel said in a report released Friday. The panel, a special task force of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said the administration's plan of setting up even an interim `` Phase 1'' system all at once is too ambitious. `` In view of the technical, budgetary, political and arms control uncertainties surrounding the ballistic missile defense program, the panel recommends planning a number of steps in the technical development and deployment of a system ... rather than a single major action,'' the report said. The task force suggested the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> start by deploying 100 ground-based interceptor rockets as allowed under the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, either outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, or at <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, N.D. The next step, it said, should be deployment of a new generation of `` space surveillance systems to improve our early warning detection and assessment of a ballistic missile attack ...'' That could be followed by deployment of new, short-range interceptor missiles around <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, with the next phase consisting of `` additional bases and ground-based interceptors and improved sensors to cope with counter-measures.'' Only then would a move be made to deploy defensive weapons in space, the panel said, with the final step being the addition of ground - or space-based lasers `` This approach would allow for more confident decisions and more flexibility in the face of uncertainties and would probably not require any more time in the long run,'' the task force contended. The science board task force was asked to take a fresh look at the Star Wars program early this year by <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. Its report was dated April 13 but was not cleared for unclassified release until Friday. The Pentagon, in finally releasing the study, stressed the findings were `` solely those of the authors and the submission of the report to the secretary in no way signals a change in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy with respect to the -LRB- Star Wars -RRB- program.'' The Star Wars program, known formally as the Strategic Defense Initiative, is an effort to develop lasers and other exotic weapons that could be deployed either in space or on the ground to automatically shoot down enemy nuclear missiles. Last September, then-Defense Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> selected five Star Wars technologies for concentrated research, saying they would form the heart of an initial Phase 1 system. Among the five were some space-based as well as ground-based rocket systems. Ever since then, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has suggested the research results involving all five technologies would be evaluated sometime in the early 1990s and a decision made on constructing an initial system. `` We believe that the difficulty of supporting such a large decision all at once and of bringing all system elements to a satisfactory stage at the same time make the all-at-once plan very risky,'' the task force said. `` The stepped plan allows much more confident decisions and much more flexibility in the face of uncertainties.'' The Pentagon also should consider giving the highest priority to development `` of the sensors, processing and communications necessary'' to detect a nuclear attack and track and target incoming missiles, it said. Moreover, it said, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must resolve their dispute over what research the ABM Treaty allows. `` There is not a force acting on the SDI program that is more damaging or more insidious ...,'' the 11-member group wrote. `` Because the Soviets exploit ambiguities to the limit, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy that restricts us to activities that are unambiguously permitted by the treaty could seriously impair our security,'' the panel said. `` We believe the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> should define a technically optimum testing and deployment program and should then adhere to that program except when treaty constraints unambiguously require it to do otherwise.'' The assessment requested by <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> comes at a time when the <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary has been studying changes to the Star Wars research schedule caused by congressional budget cuts. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said earlier this month he would recommend a budget veto if the Star Wars request of $ 4.55 billion in fiscal 1989 was cut too deeply.
</TEXT>
