 The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> on Friday accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of shipping arms and military hardware to Afghan rebels and violating the agreement under which Soviet soldiers are leaving <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted ministry officials as saying <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was not living up to the April 14 <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement that prohibits it from assisting Afghan anti-government forces. In a separate commentary, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> criticized Pakistani Foreign Minister <PERSON> Zain </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> for allegedly inciting the rebels to military action. According to <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> media reports, the Afghan Foreign Ministry has complained twice this week to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is helping arm the Afghan rebels. Soviet Foreign Ministry officials said `` the shipping of arms and ammunition from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> into the territory of the Republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is an obvious violation of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreements which entered into force on May 5,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. Terms of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement mean <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> `` should discontinue the entire range of actions and activities to interfere in the affairs of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' it said. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has officially denied helping ship arms to the guerrillas but <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> said Thursday that his country will observe the policy of `` symmetry,'' in which the guerrillas receive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid as long as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> arms the Marxist government. Soviet soldiers began withdrawing May 15 and the first convoy to leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> crossed the border Wednesday. According to the agreement, all of the estimated 115,000 Soviet soldiers must be withdrawn within nine months. A Soviet journalist indicated Thursday that between 12,000 and 15,000 Soviet soldiers had been killed in fighting since Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979. In its commentary, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> promised Soviet officials on a recent trip to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that his country would abide by the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement, but said on his return home Thursday that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will continue to help the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> aid the rebels. commentator <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Vavilov </PERSON> said. The Afghan peace process requires strict observance of all its terms, and `` any deviations, and ` free' and ` broad' interpretations of separate articles and clauses of the accords are intolerable,'' said commentator <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Vavilov </PERSON> said. He quoted Western press reports as saying unprecedented arms shipments were en route to the border of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, where the Afghan insurgents have their bases.
