<HEAD>Former Newsman Dies of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, who resigned as managing editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Honolulu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Bulletin </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 after revealing he was suffering from AIDS, died Friday at his home in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. He was 39. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> resigned from the Star-Bulletin on Sept. 2, 1986, saying he was unable to continue working because he was suffering from Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome. `` As a journalist, I have spent my career trying to shed light in dark corners,'' he wrote in revealing his illness in an editorial page article on the day of his resignation. `` AIDS is surely one of our darkest corners. It can use some light. `` By writing about AIDS, I am following a tradition of journalists who have written about their illnesses to help educate and, if blessed by finding the right words, to help others with the disease feel less alone,'' he wrote. `` Most of all, I am writing to say if we do n't want to be treated as a pariah, we have to stop acting like one,'' he said. During his tenure at the Star-Bulletin, <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> fought for reporters' access to government records and meetings so they could keep the public informed. He served as president of the <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> chapter of <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chi </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION>, and as chairman of its <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> joined the Star-Bulletin in January 1984 after serving five years as city editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Courier-Journal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisvlle </LOCATION>, Ky. He was a 1971 graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION>. He is survived by his parents, <PERSON> Homer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>. Services will be held in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>.
