<HEAD>Reagan Signs Bill Approving Radioactive Waste Compact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed federal legislation Thursday approving the Appalachian States Low-Level Radioactive Waste Compact but warned the compact commission against attempting to enforce federal laws. In a statement announcing his signature, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said more than three quarters of the states have now entered compacts on low-level radioactive waste. He said such actions `` underscore this nation's commitment to take those actions needed to ensure the future availability of nuclear power as an energy supply option for this country.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> objected, however, to a provision of the bill assigning federal law enforcement responsibility to the commission without requiring that commissioners be appointed consistently with the appointments clause of the Constitution. `` Any effort by the commission to enforce federal regulations would contravene the Constitution,'' the president said. `` While I hope that no such effort would occur, I expect the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to take note of and report to the attorney general on any such actions of the commission in this area.'' Under the compact _ which includes <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> _ the four states are required to ensure that there is a regional facility sufficient to dispose of the region's low-level waste, and that each state has equal access to it The commission created under the compact is empowered to set regulations on waste disposal and to impose fines or other penalties for violations. During consideration of the bill, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that this part of the bill was unconstitutional because it applied to federal as well as state regulations. The department said enforcing federal regulations pursuant to a congressionally approved interstate compact constitutes the exercise of `` significant authority pursuant to the laws of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' In order to do this, the department said, the compact members would have to be appointed by the president or by other federal authorities designated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, as provided in the Constitution. Instead, the commission members are appointed by the states. In a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the governors of the compact states said they did not believe a constitutional issue would arise because `` the compact was never intended to apply to activities over which the federal government has exclusive jurisdiction.''
</TEXT>
