<HEAD>Peres Says Peace Process Alive, But Differences With Soviets
Persist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Roles, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI C. RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said Friday the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has agreed to join an international peace conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and reiterated his belief that peace would come to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. However, <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, who returned home from a 13-day trip, said many problems remained with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Also Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> reported that President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> commuted the sentences of three Jewish underground members from life in prison to 15 years for staging a deadly gun and grenade attack at <ORGANIZATION> Hebron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1983. Three Palestinians were killed and 33 were wounded in the attack. The three convicted men _ <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Livni </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shaul </PERSON> <PERSON> Nir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharbaf </PERSON> _ were among 25 Jews arrested in 1984 and charged with planning or carrying out attacks against Arab targets. In other developments: _ <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops shot and wounded a 15-year-old Palestinian during a demonstration in Jabaliya refugee camp, officials at <LOCATION> Shifa </LOCATION> hospital in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> said The youth was shot in the hand after protesters threw stones at <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops. _ The army command said a border policemen was slightly injured by a knife-wielding <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> woman in <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> _ The army confirmed that 1,770 Palestinians are being held in administrative detention but the chief military attorney, Brig Gen. <PERSON> Amnon </PERSON> <PERSON> Shtresnov </PERSON>, denied the arrests without trial were a violation of human rights. During his trip, <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, where he attended the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He met with key Soviet officials in <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubinin </PERSON>. In an interview at <ORGANIZATION> Ben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gurion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the Soviets agreed to an international peace conference which would not have the power to impose an agreement on the parties. However, he said, `` the argument with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has not reached a conclusion.'' One major disagreement concerns <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s insistence on the right of the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> to self-determination. Both Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> reject establishment of an independent Palestinian state in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told a group of supporters at the airport that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would always insist on three points: defensible borders; refusal to talk to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and refusal to give up all of the territories occupied in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. He said that during his travels, he tried to improve <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s image abroad `` Our situation is very difficult, especially with the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> said. `` I tried to present a balanced picture of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in front of the world.'' An Arab uprising broke out in the occupied territories on Dec. 8, and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s strong measures to quash the insurrection drew world criticism. <PERSON> Shtresnov </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television in reporting on the detainment of Palestinians that the army closely examined each suspect before making the arrest and gave detainees the right to appeal. He said the detentions `` are in accordance with Israeli and international law.'' He denied charges that the military justice system had collapsed under the weight of the mass arrests which took place after the uprising began. <PERSON> Shtresnov </PERSON> conceded that there were problems initially in locating and identifying detainees, but said these were quickly solved and that computers were now being used to keep track of jailed Palestinians. <PERSON> Lea </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemel </PERSON>, an Israeli lawyer who represents Palestinian prisoners, described the situation as `` a big mess.'' According to estimates by left-wing legislator <PERSON> Deddi </PERSON> <PERSON> Zucker </PERSON>, 8,100 Palestinans are in jail after trial or pending trial, in addition to 1,900 other detainees.
