<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>US and Panamanian Negotiators Agree on a Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Panamanian negotiators have tentatively agreed on a deal that calls for Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> next August and stay away until May 1989 and gives him a role in setting up a transition government beforehand, an administration official said Friday. In return for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s departure, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would agree to drop federal drug smuggling indictments against him, said the official, who has followed the negotiations but insisted on anonymity. The agreement, subject to final approval by both governments, allows <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to return to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> for holidays and to go back permanently after presidential elections set for May 1989, said the official, who described himself as opposed to the arrangement. He said Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has expressed reservations. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, said Friday that the vice president <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opposes negotiating with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> over the conditions under which <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> might surrender power. `` The administration sources who have suggested that the vice president favors ending the negotiations and bringing the envoy back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are essentially correct,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had lunch with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Friday, but the vice president's aides would not say whether they discussed the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> negotiations. The official who discussed the tentative deal also said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> recall deputy assistant secretary <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> has spent virtually all of May in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> trying to work out an agreement. The official who disclosed the tentative agreement to an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter said, `` If it gets accepted, it gives <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> everything he wants.'' The official said there were no assurances that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was negotiating seriously and he raised the possibility that the defense chief has no intention of resigning his post, as the agreement specifies. If the deal receives final approval, the official said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would be in a position to leave his associates in positions of authority because he will be able to influence the formation of the transition government. Late Friday, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> was returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for consulations. He said <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON>'s return does not mean any change in the process. `` The process continues,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said, declining further comment. Associates of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> have said in recent weeks that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> sees Aug. 12 as an appropriate time to resign because that is the fifth anniversary of his accession as commander of the Defense Forces.
