<HEAD>Artsfest Opens 17-Day Run With Samba, Brass Fanfare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The staccato beat of a samba band sounded in front of City Hall on Friday as this old Southern port unveiled the 12th edition of its <ORGANIZATION> Spoleto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> arts showcase. About 1,000 people looked on as schoolchildren sent dozens of colored balloons lofting into a pale blue sky. Then the musicians, in white slacks and metallic silver shirts, played a variety of drums and tambourines as they spun and danced on a platform stage. An hour later, the strains of a chamber music concert sounded at the nearby Dock Street Theater, the first of dozens of performances indoors and out throughout <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> over 17 days. The festival was founded by composer <PERSON> Gian </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Menotti </PERSON> and is named after the similar festival he founded in <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Friday's opening ceremonies also kicked off four days of events celebrating the bicentennial of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s ratification of the Constitution. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Way </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the chairman of the <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> board, noted people sometimes take the Constitution for granted and, in the same way, he would like to see the day when folks take the festival for granted. `` Right now, after 12 years, we are still a very fragile organization. We're still a fragile dream that becomes a reality for 17 marvelous days,'' he said. <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> called the festival <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>'s `` great contribution to the nation and the world,'' adding `` we make this gift proudly and happily.'' But he said the festival `` is not given to this city. It is earned. And each year we must strive to earn it anew.'' During the course of the festival there will be 700 performances by 2,000 performers, including productions staged in <LOCATION> Piccolo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION>, the city's companion arts festival, <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the chief judge of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, spoke briefly about the Constitution, saying that when the American experiment is measured against the ideals of its framers, it may have fallen short. `` But when you measure the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> against the other nations of the world, one can not but be amazed at how well it has worked,'' he said. The samba band was part of the cast of `` The Warrior Ant,'' a work by director <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruer </PERSON> and composer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Telson </PERSON> which features over 50 dancers, musicians and actors and which will have its premiere during <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION>. The festival's major opera, <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON>'s `` Rusalka,'' which is seldom performed in this country, was to open Friday evening. <PERSON> Menotti </PERSON> said later he feels the <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> production, splashed with special effects, will be well received. `` It is beautiful work, very melodic ... the story has magic,'' he said. `` It is done very simply like a Japanese play. I think people will come from all over the country to see our production.'' Festival General Manager <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Redden </PERSON> said that over $ 1 million in tickets had been sold by the opening of the festival. The festival has a $ 3.7 million budget and about half that total is generated through earned income, he said.
