<HEAD>Call for Boycott of `24 Horas' News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A citizens' group is calling for a boycott of the major news program in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, accusing it of dedicating 97 percent of its time the presidential candidate of the governing party. The Active and Peaceful Civic Resistance organization distributed handbills calling on the public to stop watching 24 <ORGANIZATION> Horas </ORGANIZATION>, the nationally broadcast news program of the private <ORGANIZATION> Televisa </ORGANIZATION> network. It said news of candidate <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> dominated the broadcasts. `` The public has a right to choose with its preference or rejection of the type of information that it wants to receive,'' the handbills say. `` Let the public make it's decision and maintain it until it can be proven that these news shows have stopped being instruments of one party and have become true outlets of objective information,'' the handbills conclude. No one was immediately available at <ORGANIZATION> Televisa </ORGANIZATION> offices to comment on the boycott call. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> deGortari, candidate of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> known as the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, is certain to win the July 6 elections over five minority party candidates. <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermejo </PERSON>, who identified himself as Civic Resistance's training director, said in a phone interview Friday that the group is an independent non-partisan organization in 29 Mexican cities He said it formed in 1986 after controversial elections in the northern border state of <LOCATION> Chihuahua </LOCATION>, won by the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> and considered a major setback to the opposition <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Televisa </ORGANIZATION> reorganized its news programs in response to numerous complaints of biased coverage in the <LOCATION> Chihuahua </LOCATION> elections, adding an evening news program that it said would emphasize provincial coverage and add additional viewpoints. Minority candidates have complained frequently that they are prevented from equal access to broadcast media and newspapers but President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> and other <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> and government leaders reject the accusation. Civic Resistance did not explain how it arrived at the figure of 97 percent of 24 <ORGANIZATION> Horas </ORGANIZATION>' programming being dedicated to <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>. A study done by the government's Channel 11 found that 24 <ORGANIZATION> Horas </ORGANIZATION> in February dedicated 67 bites, or 86 percent, of its campaign coverage to <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Autonomous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>. In an interview in this week's <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> magazine, <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON> attributed the heavy coverage to `` the political ties that exist between the heads of this communications enterprise and the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> and the insistence by the party that <ORGANIZATION> Televisa </ORGANIZATION> provide coverage of the <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> candidate.''
</TEXT>
