<DATELINE>TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Cuban prisoner who lost 21 -LCB- pounds while fasting for three weeks to protest his possible deportation is being force-fed, officials said. <PERSON> Esteban </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzo-Mart </PERSON> `` offered no resistance,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Talladega </ORGANIZATION> federal correctional institution. `` He's being fed liquids intravenously.'' The feeding began Thursday following an order that day by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hancock </PERSON> acted after the chief of health programs at the hospital, Dr. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanmore </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Manzo-Mart </PERSON> was `` increasingly dehydrated, and was experiencing progressive decline in his blood pressure.'' The doctor said the prisoner showed `` every sign of approaching a life-threatening situation.'' <PERSON> Manzo-Mart </PERSON> was one of 14 Cubans served with deportation papers at <ORGANIZATION> Talladega </ORGANIZATION> April 29. He began the hunger strike two days earlier and was joined by another <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> prisoner, although the second man later halted his fast. <PERSON> Manzo-Mart </PERSON> has appealed his deportation. Ten other Cubans have been served with deportation papers since Manzo-Mart and the others were notified last month. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said there are 77 Cuban detainees at <LOCATION> Talladega </LOCATION>, all of whom were in prisons in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, when rioting over deportation orders began last November.
