<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State officials said Friday they found no evidence that rooms in a welfare hotel had been divided into `` tiny cubicles,'' and said it was acceptable for two families to share a bathroom. Social Services Commissioner <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Perales </PERSON> rejected charges by the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of illegal and substandard conditions at the <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION> Hotel in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. But a Legal Aid lawyer said <PERSON> Perales </PERSON> was wrong and pledged a lawsuit. `` To call a room that's 9-by-12 not a cubicle is no consolation to a family living in it,'' said the lawyer, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON>. `` State regulations require that rooms in which homeless families are placed contain private bathrooms,'' <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> said. `` Even the commissioner conceded today that these rooms do not have private bathrooms.'' <PERSON> Perales </PERSON> ordered an investigation after Banks charged this week that as many as 80 rooms at the <LOCATION> Martinique </LOCATION> had been subdivided into 9-by-12-foot cubicles and lacked sufficient furniture. City officials and a hotel co-owner said some two-room suites used in the past by one large family had been split up for two smaller families, and that bathrooms were shared legally. <PERSON> Perales </PERSON> said the same Friday. `` We observed no evidence of new construction or of rooms being divided into tiny cubicles, and we observed no evidence of major infestations of roaches or rats.'' While some suites were split, with bathrooms shared, `` each family has a private entrance,'' <PERSON> Perales </PERSON> said. `` Each bathroom can be locked on both sides to ensure total privacy.'' Banks said the issue was not new construction and he had not alleged rat or roach infestations, but that families were being crammed into small rooms and forced to share bathrooms. The city houses 5,189 homeless families, of which 3,437 are in hotels and the rest in shelters. It recently announced a plan in which it hopes to have homeless families out of all welfare hotels in five years.
