<HEAD>US and Panamanian Negotiators Agree on a Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Combines pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Panamanian negotiators have tentatively agreed on a deal that calls for Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> next August and stay away until May 1989 and gives him a role in setting up a transition government beforehand, an administration official said Friday. In return for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s departure, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would agree to drop federal drug smuggling indictments against him, said the official, who has followed the negotiations but insisted on anonymity. The agreement, subject to final approval by both governments, allows <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to return to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> for holidays and to go back permanently after presidential elections set for May 1989, said the official, who described himself as opposed to the arrangement. He said Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has expressed reservations. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, said Friday that the vice president <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opposes negotiating with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> over the conditions under which <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> might surrender power. `` The administration sources who have suggested that the vice president favors ending the negotiations and bringing the envoy back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are essentially correct,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had lunch with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> Friday, but the vice president's aides would not say whether they discussed the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> negotiations. The official who discussed the tentative deal also said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> recall deputy assistant secretary <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> has spent virtually all of May in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> trying to work out an agreement. The official who disclosed the tentative agreement to an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter said, `` If it gets accepted, it gives <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> everything he wants.'' The official said there were no assurances that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was negotiating seriously and he raised the possibility that the defense chief has no intention of resigning his post, as the agreement specifies. If the deal receives final approval, the official said <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> would be in a position to leave his associates in positions of authority because he will be able to influence the formation of the transition government. Late Friday, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> was returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for consulations. He said <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON>'s return does not mean any change in the process. `` The process continues,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said, declining further comment. Associates of <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> have said in recent weeks that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> sees Aug. 12 as an appropriate time to resign because that is the fifth anniversary of his accession as commander of the Defense Forces. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> view is that dropping the indictments against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is a defensible bargaining position because he can not be extradited so long as he remains in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. It contends that if <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s price for leaving <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is dismissal of the indictments, this would be a low cost way of resolving the 12-week old crisis, which has dropped U.S.-Panamanian relations to a low point and produced economic collapse in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. According to a published report earlier this week, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would reserve the right to reinstate the indictment once <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> returns to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been calling on <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to step down since the indictments were returned on Feb. 5. President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on Feb. 25 but was ousted himself the following day by the pro-Noriega <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to recognize <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as the legitimate authority in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. A series of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions have contributed to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s economic demise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> apprehensions about <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> were heightened on Thursday when a pro-government newspaper published photographs of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> employees and their families so that Panamanians will `` know the Gringos who are starving us to death.'' The supplement in the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Critica </ORGANIZATION>, a propaganda organ of the government, said the Americans `` think the walls of their embassy are impregnable.'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the supplement has been `` noted with concern'' and that appropriate security measures have been taken. He declined to elaborate and refused to say whether any Americans associated with the embassy are being evacuated. `` We have seen a pattern of harassment over a period of time in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` This appears to be part of that. The way to deal with that is to continue to take the precautions that need to be taken.'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> had no comment on the negotiations. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> also refused comment except to say they were continuing.
