<HEAD>Cease-Fire Talks Falter Between Sandinistas And Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 U.S.-backed Contra rebels have still not responded to a government proposal to extend the civil war cease-fire past the May 30 deadline, Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinico </PERSON> said Friday. `` They still have n't answered a government proposal to call off for another month offensive operations,'' he said at a breakfast meeting with foreign correspondents. The leftist government and the U.S.-supplied rebels known as Contras have been exchanging charges on who's responsible for the faltering peace plan to end more than six years of war. Almost two months after the two sides signed the pact, they agree only on the desire to end the fighting. The government has warned it will stage the largest offensive to date if the cease-fire is not extended after May 30 or if no progress is made. The Contras, meanwhile, are suffering from infighting, a move that favors the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. From the government's point of view, the best way for the war to end would be for the enemy to self-destruct. Pro-Sandinista newspapers were giving widespread coverage to the Contra bickering. At the same time, the government last weekend cautioned private radio station directors against broadcasting news that violates the public order law and warned of permanent suspension. Radio station directors called the warning a `` direct threat'' and described it as self-censorship that replaces the harsh media restrictions withdrawn by the government to comply with last August's regional peace plan. The problems surrounding the cease-fire plan appear to have started almost immediately after the March 23 signing. All of the meetings held since then have been marked by mutual distrust. The government announced on Wednesday a tentative agreement for a new round of peace talks to be held May 25-28, but the Contras immediately disagreed. The years of civil war have left deep scars in this nation of 3 million. Families are divided; sons have gone off to fight with one side or the other. If all had gone according to plan, the war would just about be over and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> would be well on its way to full democracy. A state security officer argued recently that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> already was a democracy. His comments came minutes after police hauled off several opposition political leaders who spoke to journalists near a building where workers staged a hunger strike. Because the cease-fire plan has not moved forward, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have not freed more than 3,000 political prisoners nor permitted the Contras to have a say in internal politics. Talks with the internal opposition political parties stand at an impasse. The meetings were suspended by the opposition as a show of support for the strikers. The government responded by saying it would consider whether future talks would be held. According to the cease-fire plan, the first measures should have been completed by April 15. In exchange, the Contra rebels would have gathered in agreed upon cease-fire zones and been permitted to receive humanitarian aid through a neutral organization. The Sandinistas have said the insurgents could now receive food, medicine and clothes distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. But the Contras rejected that, saying the organization sympathizes with the government. `` The tactics used at the last meeting were almost to torpedo the agreement,'' Contra spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` They put into question everything we had agreed upon.'' Meanwhile, thousands of rebel troops, according to sources, moved toward the northern border. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> is providing supplies to the Contras through <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. A group of rebellious Contras has demanded the ouster of the top Contra military officer, Col. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>, a former officer under the ousted dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, the Contra's main spokesman, said recently the talk of divisions was exaggerated. Nicaraguan Vice President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said Sunday that the Contra infighting puts into doubt future cease-fire negotiations. `` In <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> the mercenary forces -LRB- the Contras -RRB- are on the verge of civil war,'' he said. `` The political heads that come here to negotiate have very little influence.'' The people, meanwhile, are war weary. The Sandinistas continue to draft youths into the military. The economy is in shambles. And farmers who fled the war zones in the northern mountains can not yet go home to plant.
