<HEAD>Senate GOP Group Says Displaced Workers Getting Inadequate
Assistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's displaced workers are not receiving adequate job search assistance, training, counseling or benefits, a study group for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans reported Friday. The report by a task force of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> said that of the more than 1 million American workers displaced annually due to plant closings or layoffs, more than one-third of them have extended periods of unemployment while some never return to the workforce. Of those who do return, almost one-half take pay cuts and more than one-third earn less than four-fifths of what they previously had earned, according to the study group which was chaired by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, R-I. The group recommended that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enact a $ 980 million <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration proposal which would consolidate two current education and job training programs _ the Job Training Partnership Act and the Trade Adjustment Assistance Act. The new worker adjustment program is designed to serve an estimated 700,000 workers and would seek to eliminate costly duplication of effort. It would also provide substantially greater emphasis on actual retraining. The 69-page report said that poor publicity, a general lack of coordination among different federal assistance programs and a `` slow response rate'' when the programs have actually have been implemented `` have plagued the delivery and quality of assistance'' to displaced workers. Projections for the next 15 years, it said, indicate that millions of Americans are not only ill-prepared for existing jobs but will have even more difficulty finding and holding jobs in the future `` unless the work force is retrained and continuously prepared for marketplace change.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` is faced with the creation of a growing underclass, increasingly made up of former manufacturing and industrial workers without the skills to enter -LRB- the work place -RRB-,'' the report said. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> conference is an organization made of all 46 Republican senators. In addition to <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, Sens. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Durenburger </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> were members of the task force which held three field hearings of March and April of last year and conducted interviews with dislocated workers, union and business representatives, service providers and program directors.
