<HEAD>Famed WWII Agent Peter Julien Ortiz To Be Buried at Arlington
Cemetery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retired Marine Col. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Julien </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, one of the corps' most colorful and highly decorated World War II veterans, will be buried at <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> announced Friday. <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, 75, died May 16 in <LOCATION> Prescott </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, of cancer. He was the most decorated Marine to serve with the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, the forerunner of the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>. His exploits during the war were the subject of two different motion pictures: `` 13 <PERSON> Rue </PERSON> <PERSON> Madeleine </PERSON>,'' starring <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cagney </PERSON>; and `` Operation Top Secret,'' starring <PERSON> Cornel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilde </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and educated in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, received numerous decorations from the French and British governments for his exploits, in addition to two <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Crosses, the Legion of Merit and two Purple Hearts. He was best known for his work in organizing <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> resistance units and coordinating the delivery of arms, ammunition and equipment to the underground after being dropped behind the lines with a British-organized <ORGANIZATION> OSS </ORGANIZATION> team in 1943. <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, who once assisted four downed <ORGANIZATION> RAF </ORGANIZATION> pilots in escaping occupied territory, became the subject of an intense search by the German Gestapo and ultimately turned himself in to the Germans in 1944 to spare local villagers from reprisals. He spent the remainder of the war as a prisoner. <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON> will be buried with full military honors at <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION> at 1 p.m. Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. He is survived by his wife, the former <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Morlan </PERSON>, and a son, Marine Maj. <PERSON> P.J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>.
