<HEAD>Quake Fears Spur Exodus of Cambodian Refugees from Southern
California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A recent powerful earthquake and an unfounded prediction of a devastating temblor have spurred many Cambodian refugees to leave <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, members of the community said Friday. Fears have been widespread in the community since a quake Oct. 1 that measured 5.9 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, and were revived by recent publicity about a purported prediction by the 16th-century seer Nostradamus that <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> would be destroyed by a temblor. `` How many people are leaving for this I really do n't know. But people are talking about it. People are leaving, are scared,'' said <PERSON> Than </PERSON> <PERSON> Pok </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cambodian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, a center for immigrant education and vocational training that serves about 10,000 people a year. One reported estimate put the number of Cambodians who have fled at 2,000. `` My real gut feeling _ 1,000 may be more realistic,'' Than said. An estimated 35,000 Cambodian refugees live in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, mainly in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. It is the largest Cambodian community in the nation. Most came after the Vietnamese invasion of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in 1979, Than said. Until last October there had been no significant earthquake or other natural disaster in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area in the time since the Cambodians arrived. The reaction to the October quake is based in Cambodian culture, Than said. `` The Cambodian culture is a mixture of Buddhism, <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and animistic belief. They believe in the super -LRB- natural -RRB- power, the storm, the earthquake, the fire, the flood. So this theory is in the back of their mind. They think they can not control; they just fear,'' he said. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 200 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said that 343 people of <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> ethnicity have been added to the welfare lists since last October. `` That is unusual growth,'' he said, although he did not know whether quake fears were behind the influx. <PERSON> Namany </PERSON> <PERSON> Keam </PERSON>, operator of the private <ORGANIZATION> Cambodian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Translation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, said she did not know anyone who had moved, but there has been a great deal of talk about people leaving to join friends and relatives in such places as <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Everybody is scared. Some of them just move. ... They'd rather go to the cold states than the earthquake state,'' she said. Impetus to the exodus apparently also came from publicity about a video, `` The Man Who Saw Tomorrow,'' in which a filmmaker interpreted a vague prediction by <PERSON> Nostradamus </PERSON> to mean <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> would be destroyed by an earthquake in May. The purported prediction was dismissed both by scientists and experts on Nostradamus. `` Cambodian culture really believes that ... somone can tell the future,'' Ms. <PERSON> Keam </PERSON> said. `` When they talk about the fortune teller in the newspaper and TV, they really believe.'' Than agreed that such fears can be triggered by things such as children being put through earthquake drills at school and the frequent discussion of earthquake preparedness in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` This kind of thing, unless you make an effort to communicate to people, they're never going to understand it,'' he said. Than said he was n't certain whether the refugees were leaving permanently. <PERSON> Vora </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanthoul </PERSON>, associate executive director of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cambodian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> office in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION>, said, `` There are some fears around. To actually leave because of that fear, there's only a small percentage. He cautioned that exact estimates would be unreliable because there is also migration north for economic reasons. `` People are moving. Quite a few businessmen are going up there because of the opportunity, because <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, as far as the <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> population, is growing,'' he said.
