<HEAD>Congressional Negiotators Compromise on New Prescription Drug
Benefit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators reached tentative compromise Friday on a new Medicare prescription drug benefit that could clear the way for final votes on a catastrophic health insurance bill next week. Rep. <PERSON> Fortney </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, D-Calif., told reporters the drug issue was the most complicated item separating <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members of a conference committee Asked when the committee would have a final compromise ready for submission to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Start </PERSON> said, `` I hope next week.'' But Stark noted that several other issues are outstanding, including the precise way flat and sliding-scale premiums will be imposed on the 31 million Medicare beneficiaries to pay for additional benefits and whether participation in the expanded coverage will be mandatory or voluntary. The tentative drug compromise being recommended by an eight-member working group to the full conference committee calls for the new benefit to be phased in starting Jan. 1, 1991. Medicare does not now cover any outpatient drugs except for a handful of particularly costly medications such as anti-rejection drugs for transplant recipients. Under the recommended compromise, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> would pay half the cost of prescriptions in 1991 after a $ 600 deductible is met. Medicare would pay 60 percent of drug costs the following year and 80 percent in subsequent years _ but still only on that portion that exceeds $ 600 a year. The premiums charged beneficiaries to cover the new benefit would be indexed each year to cover the cost of the program, which is expected to grow each year. The initial level of those premiums and details of the indexing are to be worked out in subsequent negotiations of the full conference committee. The full conference also has to resolve several other, albeit less thorny, differences. However, there is broad support for the legislation and negotiators expressed confidence at their first public meeting earlier this month that a compromise would be reached quickly. Both bills passed their respective houses by overwhelming margins and are patterned after the basic framework proposed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Neither measure makes provisions for long-term nursing home care under <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, but would shield <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> beneficiaries against financially crippling out-of-pocket doctor and hospital bills. While the cap on how much beneficiaries would have to pay is one of the issues still to be resolved, it is expected to be between $ 1,043, the latest <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> offer, and $ 1,370, the latest <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> offer. Medicare would pick up all hospital and physician costs for a beneficiary after the cap is met in a given year. <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> now pays full costs of only 60 days of a hospital stay in a given year, minus a first-day deductible, and pays only 80 percent of doctor bills, no matter how high they range. On the cost side, the major disagreement is how to distribute the additional premium <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> enrollees will have to pay _ particularly the so-called supplemental premium that is tantamount to an income tax surcharge for the estimated 60 percent of retirees who would be subject to it. Each beneficiary will have to pay a flat monthly premium for the catastrophic coverage, but about 40 percent do not have enough income to make them also subject to the sliding-scale supplemental premium that will be based on their ability to pay and be collected through the income tax system.
</TEXT>
