<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> plans to convert its largely ceremonial presidency into an elected post with executive powers and <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> seems likely to seek that role after he retires as prime minister. Confirmation that an elected president is in the works was made in parliament Thursday. Legislation described as `` only a very preliminary draft which needs considerable revision and improvements,'' has been prepared, said <PERSON> Phua </PERSON> <PERSON> Bah </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a senior parliamentary secretary. <PERSON> Phua </PERSON>'s brief statement was a written reply to a question submited by <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> See </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, the only opposition member of parliament. It ended four years of speculation that basic changes were planned in the way this bustling island republic is governed. The president is now named by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to a four-year term. Wee <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wee </PERSON>, 72, a former diplomat and journalist, has been president since 1985. In his national day address in 1984, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said the constitution might be changed to prevent any future government from squandering <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s ample reserves. He said an elected president with veto power over access to these assets might be the answer. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> has for years said he would like to follow the example of many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporate leaders and step down at 65. He reaches that age on Sept. 16. <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chok </PERSON> <PERSON> Tong </PERSON>, 46, who was named first deputy prime minister after the 1984 elections, is positioned to succeed <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. The prime minister's eldest son, Trade and Industry Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsien </PERSON> <PERSON> Loong </PERSON>, 36, is also regarded as eventual prime ministerial materi