<HEAD>WWII Vets No Longer Need Prove Atomic Radiation Caused Illnesses</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 3 grafs to show how many veterans affected and at
what cost. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The legislation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed legislation Friday making it easier for hundreds of thousands veterans to receive disability benefits for exposure to radiation from the World War II atomic blasts in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> or from nuclear test explosions. Ordinarily, veterans claiming disability benefits must prove the disability was connected with their military service. The bill bypasses this requirement for a limited group of veterans with respect to specified diseases. It applies primarily to cancer of various organs. The Office of Management and Budget said more than 300,000 veterans would be affected by the legislation, and the first-year cost was estimated at $ 65.6 million. The legislation affects veterans who served with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces occupying <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. It covers the period from Aug. 6, 1945, when the atomic bomb was dropped on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, through July 1, 1946. Also covered are veterans held as prisoners of war in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> during World War II, or who served on active duty in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> immediately following such internment if they were subject to exposure to radioactivity comparable to that of the veterans who served at <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION>. The bill also applies to veterans who participated in tests involving atmospheric detonation of a nuclear device. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION>, called the new law `` a long overdue step toward taking care of a very large and serious problem.'' `` Deadly legacies of radiation exposure hang heavily over every American community,'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said. The legislation would apply only to ailments that manifest themselves within 40 years after the veteran's last possible exposure to the specified sources of radiation or, in the case of leukemia, 30 years afterward. This period already has passed for veterans who served in <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> or were prisoners of war in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` Enactment of this legislation does not represent a judgment that service-related radiation exposure of veterans covered by the act in fact caused any disease, nor does it represent endorsement of a principle of permitting veterans to receive benefits funded through veterans programs which bear no relationship to their former military service,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` Instead, this act gives due recognition for the unusual service rendered by Americans who participated in military activities involving exposure to radiation generated by the detonation of atomic explosives. The nation is grateful for their special service, and ... -LRB- this bill -RRB- makes clear the nation's continuing concern for their welfare.
</TEXT>
