<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> told Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in December 1983 of allegations that officials in his country were connected to drug trafficking, but he also told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the charges were untrue, a top <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide present at the meeting said Friday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s national security adviser, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, said that then-Panamanian President <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Espriella </PERSON> mentioned the allegations at the end of a meeting in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, now the de facto ruler of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, attended the meeting, <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said. `` The vice president said he had not been aware -LRB- of the charges -RRB- or he would have raised them'' with de la Espriella, <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> testified in a sworn deposition for a private civil lawsuit. `` We did nothing to follow that up'' after returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was then chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interdiction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> also testified that he was aware at the time that the government of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> had been helpful to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in getting military supplies to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he had no reliable information connecting <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to the drug trade until <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted in February on drug charges by two <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> grand juries. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s testimony came during a day-long deposition as part of a $ 24 million suit by the <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a liberal policy group, charging that a list of defendants, some of whom were involved in the Iran-Contra affair, supplied the Contras with weapons in trade for cocaine, and conspired in a failed attempt to assassinate a maverick Contra field commander, <PERSON> Eden </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastora </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON>, voiced repeated objections throughout the day to the questioning, charging that it ranged far from the subject matter of the suit and was being done for political purposes. `` I think it's quite clear you have some other agenda in mind,'' he said at one point to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Withey </PERSON>, an attorney for the plaintiffs. On Thursday, another <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide, Col. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, invoked executive privilege and declined to answer when asked during a similar deposition what <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON>, discussed about narcotics at a Dec. 16, 1985, meeting. When <PERSON> Withey </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> about the same meeting on Friday, he agreed to discuss it but said his recollection was not specific. `` I think we came away from the meeting with Ambassador <PERSON> Briggs </PERSON> with the sense that <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was a growing problem _ politically, militarily and possibly in the drug area,'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> testified. But he said any drug problems involving <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> `` were not highlighted'' by <PERSON>