 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. It was difficult to understand at times, but the jury was given a transcript. Another call at about 11:30 p.m. Sept. 2 includes a recording of Small reading instructions to his wife for delivery of the cash. The money was raised and the family was prepared to pay the ransom, said Mrs. Small, but the quality of the recording was so poor she could not understand all the instructions for delivery. `` I could hear another voice in the background swearing,'' Mrs. Small testified. `` Then I realized it was <PERSON> Steve </PERSON>'s voice. He was giving me instructions ... where to take the money.'' Small told his wife that after the cash was delivered and counted, a map would be mailed to her giving directions to the burial site. Mrs. <PERSON> Small </PERSON> said the kidnapper's voice came on the telephone and she tried to get clarification of the delivery orders, but soon `` he just hung up the phone.'' Small was lured by a telephone call from the family's Victorian home near the <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> shortly after midnight Sept. 2, 1987. Previous testimony has linked <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> to the coffin-sized box, which witnesses said they saw him building, and to a public telephone at about the time a ransom call was being recorded by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. The woman with whom <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> lived, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rish </PERSON>, 26, also was charged with murder and kidnapping and was awaiting trial.
