<NOTE>Eds: KwaNdebele is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court ruled Friday that women in the black homeland of <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION> must be allowed to vote and nullified all-male elections held in 1984. Justice C.F. <PERSON> Eloff </PERSON> declared invalid a proclamation signed by President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> that denied women the right to vote or sit in the homeland's legislative assembly. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and members of the legislature who opposed the court action by five <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION> women were ordered to pay costs. About 50 women wearing traditional colorful blankets attended Friday's session at <ORGANIZATION> Pretoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> KwaNdebele </ORGANIZATION> is the only of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 10 black homelands where women have not been allowed to vote. The judge also said the 1984 elections for 16 legislative seats were null and void. One of the 16 seats was captured by <PERSON> Majozi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlangu </PERSON>, who later was elected chief minister of the homeland by the assembly. Of the 77 seats in the assembly, 61 are appointed. It was not immediately clear how or when the empty seats will be filled and whether <PERSON> Mahlangu </PERSON> will be allowed to remain chief minister. <ORGANIZATION> KwaNdebele </ORGANIZATION> is an impoverished area the size of <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> with almost no resources or infrastructure. About 400,000 people live in the territory northeast of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, and many workers spend up to eight hours a day commuting to jobs in white areas. The homeland currently has `` self-governing'' status but is considering opting for independence, as four homelands already have done. <LOCATION> KwaNdebele </LOCATION> authorities have been accused of harsh treatment toward dissidents who oppose independence. Nic de Villiers of the <ORGANIZATION> Pretoria </ORGANIZATI