<SECOND>AM-Radar Readers,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Men Who Tracked Pearl Harbor Attack Gather For Reunion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the Japanese planes headed toward <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> on Dec. 7, 1941, Pfc. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockhard </PERSON> tracked mysterious blips on his radar screen on the island of <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>. `` We picked up a huge indication on the scope of something. We had no idea what it was,'' he said Friday. `` We did n't know if it was a bird, Superman or a plane.'' He and another young serviceman were alone in the radar room, watching the pulsing signal move steadily toward the island. <PERSON> Lockhard </PERSON> relayed the information by telephone to a lieutenant, who brushed aside the concerns of the 19-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Signal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> radarman, noting that it was probably a squadron of B-17s en route from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` We continued to plot it and track it and called back again. I was more insistent. But nothing was done,'' he said. `` We plotted it to within 20 miles of the island, and at that point, the signal became lost in the terrain.'' Moments later, `` We had been attacked. You could see the smoke rising. We immediately knew what we had seen.'' About 3,700 American servicemen and civilians were killed in the attack. Friday, <PERSON> Lockhard </PERSON> and other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Signal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warning </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, met in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> for the first time in 47 years, and a visit to the <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in this suburb, where a model of the SCR-270 radar is on display. The device was built by <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. The SCR-270, which tracked the approach of the planes, was `` the Model T of radar,'' said <PERSON> Lockhard </PERSON>, a retired project manager at <ORGANIZATION> AMP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, a maker of electrical connections. `` Many people had faith in it, but there were also a lot of doubting <PERSON> Thomases </PERSON>. A lot of military people looked on it as a toy,'' he said. `` They did n't believe in it enough to believe it was the valuable tool that it was.'' Six radar units had been delivered to the island about three months earlier, he said. `` It was a brand new animal,'' <PERSON> Lockhard </PERSON> said. `` We had no idea it was an enemy attack, other than we thought something was wrong with the equipment. I ran it through a series of checks. `` The feeling was more like incredulity. It was phenomenal. It's one of the footnotes to history You can play out all sorts of ` what if' games. `` The real value to the whole thing, I've always felt, was it gave credibility to the equipment. Everybody recognized the potential, where some did n't before.''
</TEXT>
