<HEAD>Japan Must Offer New Ideas On Beef, Citrus Imports, U.S. Aide Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiator <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> served notice Friday that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is willing to pursue talks on opening the Japanese market for imported beef and citrus, but that it is up to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to offer new proposals. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, the deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative, was in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to attend the three-day <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, which ended Friday. He met for unofficial talks with officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, Forestry and Fisheries Thursday. On Friday, he told a news conference at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is prepared to listen, but we feel the Japanese must show more flexibility in their position. ... It is not up to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to make more proposals, but up to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.'' `` We're over here and they're over there,'' he said, adding that as a negotiator he saw no reason for optimism yet. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s semi-governmental <ORGANIZATION> Livestock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which controls imports of beef, `` interferes in the market'' and `` should stay out of our business.'' The corporation charges a 50 percent tax on imported beef before it is sold to wholesalers. He reiterated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position against surcharges on beef imports, saying such surcharges hurt foreign exporters and violate the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a Geneva-based forum for international trade disputes. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said that unlike tariffs, surcharges are unilateral measures which involve no `` swapping'' with trading partners and `` upset the balance set in tariff negotiations.'' He said surcharges fluctuate to stabilize prices and add an element of uncertainty to exporters, while tariffs are fixed and transparent. In response to a reporter's question, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> also said an increase in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s tariffs `` would seem exceedingly strange'' since tariffs are a transitional measure to cushion producers during structural changes. Instead, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> suggested that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> establish a domestic income maintenance system that would not burden foreign exporters. Though both sides have expressed a desire to settle the dispute between themselves, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has brought the issue before <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> and will keep pursuing <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> action `` until and unless there is a bilateral decision,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. An earlier U.S.-Japanese agreement setting quotas on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> beef and citrus exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> expired in March. Talks to set a new timetable for market liberalization broke down, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> took its case to <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> on May 4. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, another major exporter of beef to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, has also filed a complaint with the international body.
