 A senior government official on Friday dismissed a critical letter from a Roman Catholic leader as too confrontational, an official report said. Deputy Premier <PERSON> Matej </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> rejected the cardinal's letter at a meeting of church dignitaries and cultural officials. He said the letter `` adopts and authorizes opinions of those who actually try to misuse the interests of believers and churches for political purposes leading to pressure.'' In the letter, dated April 23, Czechoslovak Catholic primate <PERSON> Frantisek </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> demanded a new state policy toward religion. He signaled Catholics were ready to fight for religious freedom. Relations between the Communist authorities and the church have been strained over the government's refusal to allow any bishops to be appointed in the last 15 years. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> has refused to accept candidates from the state-sponsored clergy association Pacem in <LOCATION> Terris </LOCATION>. Half a million Catholics signed a petition organized by a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> lay activist in December to demand more bishops, more priests and an end to harassment for churchgoers. The cardinal, in the letter sent to Premier <PERSON> Lubomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON>, said that force used by police to break up a peaceful demonstration in <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION> in March illustrated the need for a new policy of dialogue. <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> said contacts between the state and church had reached a state of crisis. He said that <PERSON> Catholics </PERSON> who `` are conscious of their rights will demand them and are prepared to make sacrifices.'' <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON>, however, responded that `` due to its confrontation platform and tactless procedure, the letter can not create a basis for constructive relations, and the government is therefore forced to reject it.'' <PERSON> Lucan </PERSON> also complained that the letter was made available to the Western media `` as background material for new attacks.'' Authorities and the church recently reached agreement on the appointment of two bishops to assist <PERSON> Tomasek </PERSON> and an apostolic administrator for the Slovak diocese of <LOCATION> Trnava </LOCATION>. Still, 10 of the country's 13 bishops' posts remain vacant, a situation the cardinal described as `` catastrophic.'' The three bishops are all over 75.
