of years from 350 to 150. Picks up 6th graf pvs, In an .. .</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Lehder, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conviction of Colombian drug trafficker <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON> received scant attention in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s press Friday with most papers concentrating on <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s 3-1 soccer victory over <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>. None of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s 20 daily newspapers ran editorial comment on the case and several did not mention the case at all. No public demonstrations for or against the conviction were reported. Indeed, the legal aspects of the case drew the most attention. Former Justice Minister <PERSON> Felio </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrade </PERSON> said Friday that a U.S.-Colombia treaty limits to 30 years the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sentence that may be imposed on convicted drug traffickers extradited from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, echoing a point that <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s lawyer tried to make in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s seven-month trial in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, ended Thursday when he was convicted of smuggling 3.3 tons of cocaine and of related charges. He faces up to life plus 150 years in prison and $ 350,000 in fines when he is sentenced July 20. In an interview with the radio chain <ORGANIZATION> Caracol </ORGANIZATION> former <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Andrade </PERSON> said, `` The Colombian government should make a case in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts to the effect that a Colombian citizen can not be sentenced ... to a term not encompassed by Colombian law.'' The maximum sentence in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> is 30 years in prison. Another former justice minister, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </P