<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The furor over expensive yachts confiscated for as little as a single marijuana cigarette has led the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to review, but not abandon, the `` zero tolerance'' anti-drug policy. Civil libertarians have attacked the seizures as unconstitutional, arguing searches are often illegal and owners are being punished for something done by others. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said Friday the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION>, which explored the wreck of the Titanic, was the latest confiscated vessel to be returned to its owners. The ship was seized in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> when a crewman was found with a small amount of marijuana. `` The Atlantis II is being given back because the owners were perfectly innocent, and they're actually shocked because they were trying to improve their security,'' said <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON>. The crewman pleaded guilty Thursday to misdemeanor drug possession and was sentenced to a year of unsupervised probation and fined $ 100, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleming </PERSON>, a Los Angeles-based Customs spokesman. Under an agreement reached Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> II </ORGANIZATION> will resume scientific expeditions technically under Customs' control while its owner, the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, petitions the seizure, he said. Privately, Customs officials have expressed anger at the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>'s highly publicized aggressive seizures of boats. `` They are destroying the program,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs