<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A western cold front spawned thunderstorms, high winds and hail over most of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and central <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Friday, while the rain-saturated East Coast got still more precipitation. Severe thunderstorms blanketed the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, with clusters of showers over central <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, as well as eastern <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> to southwest <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. Residents in <LOCATION> Hobbs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, reported seeing two tornadoes touch down Friday. One twister tore part of the roof and a side from a building, uprooted trees, knocked down telephone poles and overturned a pickup truck, slightly injuring the driver. The second tornado destroyed an unoccupied mobile home, and tore off parts of the roofs of two houses, a witness said. The storm system brought golf ball-sized hail at Hunt and <LOCATION> Kerrville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and marble-sized hail near <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>. Showers over the central High Plains and southern and central Rockies were accompanied by blustery north winds gusting to 40 mph, sending the mercury plunging into the 40s and 50s Rain and drizzly weather continued in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, with severe storms stretching from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> to eastern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> during the afternoon and evening. In <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, where 8 inches of rain have fallen in parts of the state since Monday, a 16-year-old youth drowned Thursday night while rafting with some friends on a rain-swollen creek in <LOCATION> Fayetteville </LOCATION>, state police said. The heavy rains have cause