<HEAD>Banks Are Asked to Waive Debtor Countries' Interest Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> suggested Friday that commercial banks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries voluntarily give up $ 5 billion to $ 6 billion of interest owed them by 17 heavily indebted countries. In a special report, the bank, which is owned by 151 governments, said interest waivers of about two percentage points on the debt owed by the so-called `` middle income countries'' would generate the same financial relief in the first year as a $ 5 billion to $ 6 billion loan. The `` middle income countries'' in question are <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. They have foreign debts of about $ 500 billion. The 42-page report, `` The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the Heavily Indebted Middle-Income Countries,'' did not say how long the waivers should be continued. The same suggestion was made privately last month by <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>, the bank's president, to representatives of member countries. <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> and government financial leaders including <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, have criticized commercial banks for not lending more. The commercial banks, meanwhile, say governments and intergovernmental bodies like the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and its sister body, the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, should do more lending. The report said governments of borrowing countries are reluctant to borrow more without some relief. They complain they are already paying out $ 30 billion a year to more prosperous countries, mostly on old debt. `` In many of these countries, per capita income and consumption have fallen considerably over the past five years and are for some countries back to levels that were already attained in the early 1960s,'' according to the report. The average Argentine earned $ 2,350 in 1986, compared with $ 160 for the average Nepalese, $ 17,840 for the average Swiss and $ 17,500 for the average American, according to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s figures. The report cites <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, where 700,000 teen-agers reach working age every year and few jobs have been created since 1981. Unemployment in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> increased by 70 percent between 1981 and 1984, it says. The <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> is the largest source of aid money to nearly 120 countries, lending about $ 17 billion annually. That figure is expected to increase to more than $ 20 billion in the 1990s.
