<HEAD>Judge Blocks Testing of Prison Staff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Friday temporarily blocked <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration plans to start random drug testing of all 13,000 federal prison workers, saying the testing of `` law-abiding employees'' posed constitutional problems. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order sought by a labor union against the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION>, one of the first federal agencies scheduled to begin drug testing under President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s September 1986 executive order. `` The program would force law-abiding employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> to submit to testing even though not suspected of any wrongdoing, negligence or dereliction of duty,'' <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> said in his order. The 750,000-member American Federation of Government Employees, the largest union representing federal workers, also has challenged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s entire drug testing program, covering 345,000 employees in 40 agencies, in a separate lawsuit. The union chose the federal court in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> for both suits because of favorable precedents from the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which has ruled against post-accident testing of railroad workers. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> may resolve the issue in a case scheduled for argument this fall involving the testing of applicants for jobs and promotions in the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON>'s order blocks testing of prison workers, which had been set to start Monday, until at least next Thursday, when a hearing is scheduled on a longer-lasting preliminary injunction. The injunction, if granted, could be appealed to higher courts. <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> pressed a government lawyer, apparently without success, to bypass the preliminary injunction hearing and allow the ban to stay in effect until a full-scale trial of the lawsuit June 16. `` I do n't think the world's going to come to an end because the program is delayed until a full, careful consideration,'' the judge said. But <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lepley </PERSON> said the government was unwilling to let the temporary ban, which can not be appealed, stay in effect longer than the 20-day legal limit for restraining orders. At a hearing Thursday, <PERSON> Lepley </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> had concluded that even a few days' delay in testing `` would cause a great chance of serious injury, even death.'' Both <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> and a union lawyer questioned that claim. Under <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1986 order, federal agencies are to conduct random urinalysis testing of employees in `` sensitive'' jobs, and also test applicants for new jobs and promotions, workers involved in accidents, and supervisors. Workers who fail the tests can be fired if they decline rehabilitation and lesser discipline. The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> has declared that all its employees hold `` sensitive'' jobs and therefore are subject to random testing, with 5 to 10 percent of the staff tested each year. The <ORGANIZATION> AFGE </ORGANIZATION> suit contends the program violates constitutional standards for unreasonable searches by allowing testing without individual suspicion of drug use. The suit also claims violations of federal laws forbidding discrimination against the handicapped and requiring employee discipline to be related to job performance. In his order, <PERSON> Weigel </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and appellate rulings `` cast serious doubt upon the constitutionality and lawfulness'' of the program. The judge said his order does not prohibit testing of any prison employee based on a reasonable suspicion of drug use that impairs job performance. That is the standard the government has been following since 1985, <PERSON> Lepley </PERSON> said.
