<HEAD>Family Horrified to Find Their Loved One Cremated by Mistake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> family was horrified when they saw a stranger in the casket at a <LOCATION> Hamden </LOCATION> funeral home and found out that the man they came to mourn had been cremated by mistake, a newspaper reported Friday. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>, 68, of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, died May 9, as did <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON>, 73, of East Haven. Both men were taken first to the morgue at <LOCATION> Yale-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> and then to separate branches of <ORGANIZATION> Sisk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> funeral homes in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hamden </LOCATION>, a town about 8 miles to the north, the New Haven Register reported. <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> was to have been buried May 13 but instead was cremated. <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> was to have been cremated, but his body appeared dressed in <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>'s suit in an open coffin May 12 during calling hours at the funeral home in <LOCATION> Hamden </LOCATION>, according to the newspaper. The Eagans Thursday filed a complaint against the funeral home with the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and has hired an investigator to find out who made the error, the newspaper reported. `` There had to be an extremely large number of mistakes made in order for this to have happened,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Branford </LOCATION>, one of <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>'s three sons, was quoted as saying. `` I would never want another family to have to go through this.'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisk </PERSON>, one of the funeral home's owners, blamed <ORGANIZATION> Yale-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Haven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and said his attorney was preparing to file a complaint against the hospital, the newspaper reported. `` The tags were wrong,'' he was quoted as saying. `` They released the wrong bodies to us.'' But <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Urtz </PERSON>, a hospital spokesman, said Friday that the mixup had to have occurred at the funeral home. `` One was taken to the morgue five hours before the other man arrived in the emergency room. These individuals went to the morgue properly tagged and were properly identified,'' he said. A state medical examiner, <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>, had signed a certificate which had allowed <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>'s unintended cremation, the newspaper reported. <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON>'s daughter-in-law, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON>, was quoted by the newspaper as saying that the funeral home did not tell her family what had happened and only asked that a relative identify <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON>'s body on May 13 <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> said her husband found it strange that <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON>'s body was dressed in a stranger's suit `` We did n't know where the suit came from. No one had sent it,'' she was quoted as saying. The Eagans' attorney, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said Thursday he did not know who was responsible for the mistake but filed a complaint against the funeral home because `` they're the ones that ultimately made the arrangements.'' <PERSON> Eagan </PERSON>'s cremated remains were placed in a casket on May 13 by <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON> Funeral Home, which replaced <PERSON> Sisk </PERSON> brothers at the family's request, and were buried after a funeral mass, the newspaper reported <PERSON> Gormley </PERSON> was cremated and a memorial service for him was held at <ORGANIZATION> Sisk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper reported.
