<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hospital worker winced and shut his eyes at the pain of a young, bloodied shooting victim in <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>'s emergency room, as the little victims of a schoolhouse shooting began arriving Friday. `` It was a big trauma. Everybody was running around,'' said <PERSON> Adrian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatter </PERSON>, a supply technician who was in the emergency room when ambulance drivers said they were coming from the school in <LOCATION> Winnetka </LOCATION> with four children, victims of the shooting. Both cities are affluent northern suburbs of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` It kind of affected me because I've got kids of my own,'' <PERSON> Hatter </PERSON>, 26, said. He said he was especially moved by a young blonde girl who was shot in the wrist and chest. `` She looked like she was fighting for her life; she was rolling back and forth on the cart,'' Hatter said. `` I had to close my eyes a couple times and listen for my next orders.'' Parents of the wounded children were secluded in a room to await word and to avoid reporters. `` In view of these circumstances, they are doing remarkably well,'' Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Winchester </PERSON>, a surgeon who operated on some of the children, said of the parents. The four children _ <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Tebourek </PERSON>, 8, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Trossman </PERSON>, 6, <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, 8, and <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, 7 _ were in critical condition with neck and chest wounds, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Soohoo </PERSON>. `` It was like a zoo,'' said <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, 31, a nursing assistant at <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. `` At first, people were running everywhere. We had regular cases scheduled but we had to cancel them to make room for the patients who came in