<HEAD>Cease-Fire Talks Falter Between Sandinistas And Contras; New Date
Set</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with government comment on
date, radio interview put off at government request. PICKS up 6th
graf, `The Sandinista ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The U.S-backed Contras agreed Friday to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s proposed dates for the next round of peace talks, but the two sides suggested different sites. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosales </PERSON>, spokesman for the Nicaraguan Resistance, said in a phone interview from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> that leaders of the Contra rebels will attend two days of peace talks beginning Wednesday, as the government has proposed. He said the rebel leaders will arrive for talks at the border town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, where the agreement was reached in March for a 60-day cease-fire lasting until May 30. But Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said in a note to the rebels that the talks must be held in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. To hold the discussions outside of the capital, he said, `` is to go back in the advances that, with great difficulties, have been achieved'' in the cease-fire talks. <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> said earlier that the rebels had not yet responded to a government proposal to extend the cease-fire one month past the May 30 deadline. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, ordered <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catolica </ORGANIZATION> to pull off the air until Tuesday a news program that carried an interview with a rebel chief, according to <PERSON> Auxiliadora </PERSON> <PERSON> Echegoyen </PERSON>, director of the program. She said the suspension notice cited `` an interview which we transmitted with a rebel chief, whose pseudonym is Tigrillo, and which we monitored from another radio.'' She did not say which station had originally carried the interview. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the station should have cleared the interview with the government. <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catolica </ORGANIZATION>, which is operated by the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, was one of three privately owned radio stations barred from broadcasting news programs earlier this month because it reported a workers' strike. The Sandinista government and the Contras have been blaiming each other for the faltering peace plan to end more than six years of war. Almost two months after the two sides signed the pact, they agree only on the desire to end the fighting. The government has warned it will stage the largest offensive to date if the cease-fire is not extended after May 30 or if no progress is made. The Contras, meanwhile, are suffering from infighting, a move that favors the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. From the government's point of view, the best way for the war to end would be for the enemy to self-destruct. Pro-Sandinista newspapers were giving widespread coverage to the Contra bickering. The problems surrounding the cease-fire plan appear to have started almost immediately after the March 23 signing. If all had gone according to plan, the war would just about be over and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> would be well on its way to full democracy. Because the cease-fire plan has not moved forward, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have not freed more than 3,000 political prisoners nor permitted the Contras to have a say in internal politics. Talks with the internal opposition political parties stand at an impasse. The meetings were suspended by the opposition as a show of support for the strikers. The government responded by saying it would consider whether future talks would be held. According to the cease-fire plan, the first measures should have been completed by April 15. In exchange, the Contra rebels would have gathered in agreed upon cease-fire zones and been permitted to receive humanitarian aid through a neutral organization. The Sandinistas have said the insurgents could now receive food, medicine and clothes distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. But the Contras rejected that, saying the organization sympathizes with the government. Meanwhile, sources said thousands of rebel troops moved toward the northern border. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> is providing supplies to the Contras through <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. A group of rebellious Contras has demanded the ouster of the top Contra military officer, Col. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>, a former officer under the ousted dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, the Contras' main spokesman, said recently the talk of divisions was exaggerated. Nicaraguan Vice President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said Sunday that the Contra infighting puts into doubt future cease-fire negotiations. `` In <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> the mercenary forces -LRB- the Contras -RRB- are on the verge of civil war,'' he said. `` The political heads that come here to negotiate have very little influence.''
