<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Play Becomes a Movie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If it bombed in <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, will it play in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>? <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON> hopes so. At one theater in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the entire audience walked out on <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON>'s new anti-apartheid film, `` Saturday Night at the Palace.'' Now he's looking for a more sympathetic crowd in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` People could n't take it,'' <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON> said of the movie's South African run `` It's kind of like showing a movie of someone dying of lung cancer to an audience who are all heavy smokers. It's so real and so close. The movie is based on a real event _ a rampage by two white men at a black-run roadhouse on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. It was made into a play that ran in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON>, 40, who wrote the successful play on which the film is based, plays <PERSON> Vince </PERSON>, a white racist who winds up at a diner late one night with his nerd of a roommate, <PERSON> Forsie </PERSON>. The black manager of the roadhouse, played by <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> Award-winning actor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kani </PERSON>, is just closing up for the night. <PERSON> Forsie </PERSON> wants only to use the telephone, but <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> demands that the manager, whose name is September, reopen for business. In a scene that encompasses the last half of the movie, an increasingly ugly confrontation pits the characters, in shifting allegiances, against one another. The movie, produced and directed by South African <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, is a catharsis of sorts for <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON>, who based <PERSON> Vince </PERSON>'s character _ loud, abusive, violent _ on some of the people with whom he grew up in a small South African town The son of <LOCATION> Polish </LOCATION> immigrants, he moved to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> when he was 3 years old. `` I grew up in a kind of white racist area _ the attitudes were very deep,'' he said in a recent interview. `` And when I went to college -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Town </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- ... I was studying alongside blacks and meeting them socially, and it was a stunning transformation. Because all of the prejudices I'd grown up with suddenly melted away, and I realized I'd been living in the middle of this kind of lie. `` I ca n't watch the movie,'' he said. `` I just slide down in my seat and I'm praying for someone to get rid of this guy -LRB- <PERSON> Vince </PERSON> -RRB-. It's just too much _ it assaults and assaults and assaults. But in a way it's a story that has to be told.'' At one point in the film, <PERSON> Vince </PERSON>, the unemployed roustabout, delivers a monologue that frames the movie's political message. Enraged at the stubborn gentility of September, he roars, `` Who's he to be in charge of a roadhouse when I'm out of work? Everywhere you go, all you see is black faces. Bus drivers, bank tellers _ bloody three-piece suits, man!'' Apartheid, says <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON>, `` comes from the soul of that kind of character. It comes from fear _ it's a fear of being swamped.'' `` This character, <PERSON> Vince </PERSON>, has, I think, the central line of the -LRB- film -RRB- when he says, ` My old man said if you let a black man get the better of you, that's the end, you're finished; there's no going back.' That's his belief.'' This is a heady time for Slabolepszy and others in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s artistic community. A series of hit plays have emerged from <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> _ `` Master <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> ... and the Boys,'' `` Sarafina,'' `` <PERSON> Woza </PERSON> <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>,'' among others. South African music has become an international rage and there is an emergence of black South African art and literature. `` History is happening,'' said <PERSON> Slabolepszy </PERSON>, who yearns to someday `` make a picture of hope.'' Perhaps, he muses, there will be a `` happy accident'' in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. In the meantime, he finds his drama in turmoil.
