<HEAD>Hong Kong Chinese Fleeing to Canada and Investing Heavily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: dollar figures are U.S. unless specified as Canadian.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese first came to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as cooks and launderers in the gold rush 130 years ago. Today they flying in from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> with millions of dollars to invest in businesses and real estate. For the large majority, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is a hedge against <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s reversion to Chinese Communist sovereignty in 1997 While <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> entrepreneurs find easy entry under <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s `` investor immigrant'' program, hospitals in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> in British <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> report an increase the number of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> women who come to have babies because the infants automatically become Canadian citizens Other Chinese come as students and professionals. But the entrepreneurs and investors often get a special welcome. `` They have no problem flipping down 5 million dollars -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> $ 4 million -RRB- for a house because in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it would be 20 million -LRB- $ 16 million -RRB-,'' said Premier <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. One recent buyer was <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Ho </PERSON>, whose casino and ferry empire in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION> makes him one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s richest men. He paid 5.5 million Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 4.4 million -RRB- for a 25-room mansion on Bridle Path, <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>'s millionaire's row. Across the country in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Ka-shing </PERSON>, whose companies represent 20 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA