 1947. Today, 600,000 Canadians are of Chinese descent, including more than 200,000 in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and 175,000 in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>. At any one time, 18,000 <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> students are enrolled at Canadian universities. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> has become the leading source of immigrants to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, with 22,100 visas issued last year. `` I came in 1967,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lam </PERSON>, a 65-year-old <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> real estate magnate who has donated more than $ 5 million to <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> universities and the Sun Yat-sen Classical Chinese Garden in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, a replica of the ancient gardens of <LOCATION> Suzhou </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> pulled off the biggest real estate deal in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>'s history in 1972 and has since built a fortune as a conduit for other <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> investors `` Now we're seeing more than just flight capital,'' <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> said in an interview. `` There's a second strata of people, young professionals who see the writing on the wall for <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and are afraid.'' The Chinese Communists have agreed to allow <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to maintain its capitalist system for 50 years after the reversion of sovereignty, but many <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> are hedging against that. `` <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is seen as desirable because of its political stability and large <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> population.'' said <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Eng </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> realtor. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s `` investor immigrant'' program offers a visa in exchange for investment of 150,000 Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 121,500 -RRB- to 500,000 dollars -LRB- $ 405,000 -RRB- in approved businesses. Government figures show <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> investment under the program totaled 776 million Canadian dollars -LRB- $ 628 million -RRB- last year and created 4,500 jobs. Premier <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> said he welcomes the well-heeled arrivals. `` <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has been built by foreign capital _ over 50 percent of our manufacturing industry is foreign-owned,'' he said.
