<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 23,0797</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Short Sellers, `Bear Raiders' New Subject of Post-Crash Concern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the search for stock saboteurs and bear-market villains hiding in the aftermath of the October crash, a new group of suspects has emerged _ the short sellers, investors who bet money that prices will drop. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> have quietly been probing allegations that improper short selling may have contributed to the crash, though evidence of wrongdoing has n't yet emerged. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, which runs the over-the-counter market, is considering whether to implement restrictions on short selling. In addition, several companies have raised a post-crash clamor about alleged manipulation of their stock by users of the trading tactic. The head of one such company, <ORGANIZATION> Urgent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is co-sponsoring a conference Monday on short selling, titled `` Is Anyone Really Safe?'' Short selling in itself is n't a crime. In theory, short sellers sell borrowed stock they believe is overvalued, on the hunch the price will decline. Potential profits can be immense. For example, if a short seller borrows 100 shares at $ 1 a share and sells them, he earns $ 100 and uses the money as collateral for the borrowed shares. If the stock drops to 50 cents a share, the short seller buys 100 shares, returns the borrowed stock and pockets $ 50. Defenders of short selling argue that it injects liquidity into the market and helps all investors more accurately determine whether a touted stock is worth buying or not. `` Selling short enables market participants to adjust positions and causes stock to be more responsive,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> DaPuzzo </PERSON>, head of retail equities at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I think short selling has a lot of positive attributes.'' Critics say short selling can be disastrous to fledgling companies trying to raise capital, especially in the post-crash environment when so many investors already are avoiding the stock market. `` There's nothing illegal about selling short if you think a company is going to be in decline. What's bad is when people deliberately circulate adverse information that may be false for the purpose of causing a stock to go down,'' said <PERSON> A.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sommer </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> commissioner and securities lawyer in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lewis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Bockius </PERSON>. Foes of short selling often recall how the strategy was widely abused after Crash of 1929, when it played a central role in the `` Bear Raids'' in which speculators would relentlessly gang up on a target company, spreading lies about it to drive down the stock price. Such abuses led the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> to implement the short-sale rule, also known as the uptick rule, which theoretically prevents short sellers from mercilessly depressing a stock price. Under the rule, a short sale may be executed only if the previous sale moved the stock up at least -LRB- point, or one `` tick.'' But there are strategies for sidestepping this rule, and a debate has intensified on whether it works. Moreover, the stocks most susceptible to short-selling assaults have n't been protected by the uptick rule, since they are usually small, over-the-counter issues such as upstart high-technology or research concerns. These stocks soared in value in the 1982-87 bull market and became visible targets for short sellers. In the case of <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urgent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>, for example, founder <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> has contended that short sellers tried to destroy his company by spreading vicious rumors about its management. The stock of <ORGANIZATION> Carrington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, a drug firm working on a substance that could advance treatment for AIDS, sank after false rumors surfaced that the company was prohibited from testing in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carrington </PERSON>'s management claims short sellers spread the rumors. Still, many investment professionals believe the argument against short selling is n't persuasive and that further regulation would make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stock markets less attractive. `` We're not going to try to defend anybody who lies about a company to knock its stock down. That's wrong,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, a short-selling strategist who publishes the Overpriced Stock Service Newsletter. `` But 98 percent of the effort in the securities business is aimed at touting stocks. There's far, far more lying pushing stocks up then pushing them down.'' The real effect of short sellers, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> argues, is to expose companies that have serious deficiencies. `` People say short selling is un-American. But it's the reason <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has the best capital market in the world,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. `` You need to get a lot of opinions into the market.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
