<HEAD>Bear Stearns Re-Evaluating Index Arbitrage Position</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>'s remarks strongly supporting program trading have prompted <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to reconsider its recent move to halt its use of the controversial strategy, the firm says Bear <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON>, one of several major Wall Street firms to reduce their program trading activity, will `` re-examine its position'' in light of <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>'s remarks and other factors, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bear </PERSON> <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON>' chairman and chief executive officer, said Thursday. Bear <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON> went further than four other investment firms when it announced last week it would stop index arbitrage _ a major form of program trading _ not only for its own accounts but also for its customers. <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> halted index arbitrage for their own accounts amid concern that the popular form of program trading was at least partly responsible for the stock market's volatility. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee, said Thursday that excessive restriction of index arbitrage would limit market liquidity and tend to destabilize the market. He said `` insufficient arbitrage between cash and futures can be a destabilizing force in a declining market.'' In index arbitrage, traders use computers to buy or sell baskets of stocks with offsetting trades in stock-index futures to help them profit from brief price discrepancies. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that `` reduced arbitrage implies less connection between cash and futures markets and more price disparities across these markets.'' He also said, `` it is a mistake to single out one segment of the broad marketplace as the culprit for large and rapid price movements.'' Bear <PERSON> Stearns </PERSON><PERSON> ' </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said his firm had been `` monitoring closely the action and the liquidity problems of the stock market for the past week.'' He also pointed to other firms' `` suspension of index arbitrage activity for themselves but -LRB- continuation of -RRB- those activities for customers'' as further reason for the firm to re-evaluate its position. `` If we do decide to re-enter index arbitrage, we will consider limiting our activities to buying on a downtick and attempting to sell on an uptick in the stocks involved,'' <PERSON> Greenberg </PERSON> said in a statement.
</TEXT>
