<SECOND>PM-Market Report,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Officials Defend Stock Market Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock market crashes similar to last October's could happen again even if market procedures are changed, say the top-level federal officials who produced a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> study of the nation's financial markets The officials told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee Thursday that their proposals for changing some market procedures could do little about external factors that influence investors. Their report is being criticized by lawmakers for its lack of significant recommendations. `` We can not provide an ironclad guarantee that there will not be another Oct. 19 in our future,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, one of the report's authors. `` Unforeseen economic forces could, on their own, conceivably trigger such an event.'' The White House report, released Monday, focused on the record 508-point drop in the Dow Jones Industrial Average of last Oct. 19, and the unusually large price swings that have occurred repeatedly ever since. The report was written by <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Undersecretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairwoman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>. The officials recommended instituting a `` circuit breaker'' that would temporarily halt trading on the nation's stock, futures and options exchanges in case the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped by 250 points in a single day. That has happened only once, last Oct. 19. The report also urged that improvements be made in the credit, clearing and settlement procedures the markets use to complete transactions. But the working group suggested no limitations on computerized program trading, some forms of which have been blamed for adding to market volatility. It also failed to agree on whether to change the margins, or up-front payments, required for futures transactions. Margin requirements are lower on futures exchanges than for stock markets, which critics say causes speculation. The group ignored as well a recommendation made by an earlier <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel headed by <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, an investment banker, that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> or some other agency oversee issues that affect all markets. The working group's members have cautioned that it would be unrealistic to take steps such as curbing program trading. `` We can not go back to the days of the abacus or mechanical adding machines,'' <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> said. Lawmakers, however, accused the report of not going far enough to ease volatility and soothe worried investors. `` It is you and your panel who continue to embrace anachronistic regulatory reforms that have been outstripped by new technologies,'' said the subcommittee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass. Further criticism came from Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, of which the finance subcommittee is a part He accused the working group of having `` given birth to a mouse'' and of failing to take steps to restore investors' confidence. `` You should not come by my office when people start buying rope and heating pots of tar and collecting feathers to apply to persons ... who have sat idly by ... while the financial situation of this nation erodes,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said. The subcommittee has been holding hearings on the market's problems for months, but so far has written no legislation Asked outside the hearing room when a bill would emerge, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said, `` As soon as circumstances permit.''
</TEXT>
