<HEAD>U.S. Urged to Prosecute Oil Company For 1984 Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has asked the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to consider criminal prosecution of <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and its executives for a 1984 refinery explosion in south suburban <LOCATION> Lemont </LOCATION> that killed 17 people. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> made its request Thursday, following a finding by an administrative judge that <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION>, then called <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, violated federal health and safety regulations overseen by the <ORGANIZATION> Ocupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> is appealing <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> citations and the administrative finding to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. While it does, the company faces the prospect that it and individual employees could be found in criminal violation of federal safety regulations. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> has the right to seek criminal prosecution for such violations, but rarely has done so during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workplace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> found that <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> violations included inadequate inspections for cracks in a pressure tank that exploded, as well as poor training for its fire brigade. In addition to the 17 killed, the July 23, 1984 explosion injured 21 others. After reviewing government and company claims, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> administrative Judge R.M. Child concluded that the company `` failed to adequately inspect for the presence of cracks in pressure vessels, which exposed employees to increased likelihood of fire or explosion.'' Child also found that the company failed to use inspection techniques to determine the presence or absence of cracks and that `` this was a willful failure.'' He said the company `` willfully failed to provide fire-protective clothing to persons required to handle fires'' and `` willfully failed to provide adequate firefighting and education to its shift fire brigade.'' Child rejected one alleged violation and reduced the original fine levied against <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> to $ 22,000 from $ 31,000. Officials of Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment pending a review of the <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> action.
