<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in April, only marginally better than March's 0.5 percent gain, the government reported today. More than one-fourth of the April rise came from a steep 2.0 percent jump in clothing costs, tying March for the greatest one-month gain since price records were first kept in 1947. Grocery prices climbed at their fastest pace in 20 months, while energy prices were up sharply as well _ reflecting the steepest rise in gasoline prices since August. The April gain meant that for the first four months of 1988 retail prices were up at an annual rate of 4.5 percent. While this was little changed from the 4.4 percent for all of 1987, economists were concerned because much of the inflationary pressure has shown up in the last two months. Analysts noted that the March rise had been the most severe since January 1987. On Thursday, investors set aside worries about inflation long enough to help the stock and bond markets break their recent slides. A number of senators, meanwhile, have reaffirmed the government's pledge to stand behind deposits in the nation's savings and loan institutions after a congressional agency reported the doubling of the deficit in the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L insurance fund `` There is absolutely no doubt the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> stands behind our deposit insurance program,'' <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., said at a hearing Thursday by his panel On Wall Street, stock prices staged a partial recovery Thursday that traders attributed to `` bargain shopping'' and lessening of recent tension over inflation. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell a total of 56.54 points Tuesday and Wednesday, rose 7.63 to 1,958.72. Broader market gauges were mixed. Bond prices advanced after falling in the first three sessions this week. The price of the bellwether 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond rose nearly $ 2.50 for every $ 1,000 in face value as its yield slipped to 9.27 percent from 9.29 percent late Wednesday. In the report on thrifts, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, director of the accounting and financial management division of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said the liabilities of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> exceeded its assets by $ 13.7 billion at the end of 1987, up from $ 6.3 billion a year earlier. He also said the money available to the insurance fund _ $ 28 billion over the next 10 years _ `` probably will not be adequate'' to restore the industry's health by closing or merging 505 institutions listed as insolvent. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> estimated it would cost $ 30 billion to $ 35 billion to clean up the S & amp; L mess, which is centered primarily in Southwestern states hard hit by depressed real estate and oil markets. That estimate does not include an additional 435 `` barely solvent'' institutions, he said. In other economic developments Thursday: _ The two broadest measures of the nation's money supply rose in early May while a narrower measure fell, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> reported _ The nation's 24 largest investor-owned utilities charged their commercial and industrial electric users an average 6.28 cents per kilowatt-hour over the 12 months ended April 30, down from 6.29 cents a year earlier, a study by the consulting firm <ORGANIZA