 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> today urged the family that controls <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to consider splitting the company into two or more publishing and broadcast firms. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, who is engaged in a takeover bid for Richmond-based Media General, said at the annual stockholders meeting that his interest `` is not in taking the newspapers away'' from company Chairman <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> and his family. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> and two associates were submitted as candidates for election to the company's board of dierectors. Stockholders will vote on board members today, but the results will not be announced until later, after all proxies have been counted. One item not on the agenda for the meeting was <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s buyout offer. Media General officials rejected <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s original $ 61.50-per-share offer to buy all the company's stock. That offer was made Feb. 29, and <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> has since sweetened his bid to $ 70 a share. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> and his associates own 10.1 percent of Media General Class A stock, an investment of more than $ 111 million. Members of the <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family own 70 percent of the company's Class B stock, which controls seven of the 10 board seats The <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family also owns about 12 percent of the publicly traded Class A stock. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> is seeking to have himself, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotterer </PERSON> named Class A directors. Media General has recommended that its three directors be re-elected. The days leading up to the annual meeting were marked by charges and countercharges between the two parties. On Saturday, lawyers for Media General and <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> aired their allegations of unfair tactics in the proxy battle before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. Both sides had filed motions for injunctions to stop the opposition from delivering what they characterized as false and misleading information to shareholders. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> denied both sides' motions, calling adversaries in proxy fights `` the world's most thin-skinned people'' and saying he found no evidence of irreparable harm by either party. The judge also said the proper time for the parties to assess damages was after the annual meeting. Earlier this week, Media General officials said <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> had offered to end his attempt to land three board seats in exchange for control of the company's cable television franchises in <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Fredericksburg </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> strongly denied ever making such an offer, and called Media General's claim `` a desperate move to make it appear as though we are losing the proxy contest. In my opinion, this last-minute trick just wo n't work.''
