<FIRST>r f AM-SmithKline-Nova     05-20 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SmithKline-Nova,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>SmithKline and Nova Pharmaceutical to Market Drugs Jointly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Nova </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to a joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beckman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to develop and market a variety of painkilling and central nervous system drugs, pending approval from both firm's boards, Baltimore-based Nova announced. The preliminary agreement, estimated to be worth $ 72.5 million to <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION>, eventually will give Philadelphia-based <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> an estimated 20 percent stake in <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION>, which was founded in 1982. The two firms would be advancing work on a range of drugs Nova has developed, including a class of painkillers targeted at bradykinin, which <PERSON> Nova </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION> report plays a key role in relaying pain messages to the nervous system. The findings were reported in the current issue of the Proceedings of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is quite significant for Nova,'' <PERSON> Arda </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Minocherhomjee </PERSON>, a health-care analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Howse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Ragen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said of the joint venture. `` It gives them access to an excellent marketing partner, and, furthermore, it gives them the capital needed to develop their products.'' After the agreement was announced Thursday, <PERSON> Nova </PERSON>'s stock closed unchanged in over-the-counter trading at $ 8.25 a share. `` Nova cut a very attractive deal as far as they're concerned,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartash </PERSON>, pharmaceutical analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It's very good, and they get <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> to carry some of the development costs.'' `` You need to raise the funds when you do n't need them,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, president and chief executive of Nova, which analysts estimate had $ 2.4 million in cash and more than $ 15 million in available funds as of March 31, more than enough to finance its research and development expenses this year. For the first quarter ended March 31, the company lost $ 1.4 million, compared with a loss of $ 2 million a year ago. Revenues increased to $ 4.1 million from $ 1.6 million. Nova received <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> approval in January to start clinical testing on an analgesic that blocks the transmission of bradykinins, a powerful pain-producing substance in the body. The company is conducting clinical trials on a nasal spray form of the drug to block symptoms of the common cold and plans to seek <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approval to test the drug's effectiveness in relieving inflammation and blocking burn pain. Analysts estimate that the potential annual market for the analgesic could easily top $ 100 million three or four years after it is released. <PERSON> Nova </PERSON> also is developing compounds to treat central nervous system disorders including epilepsy, Parkinson's disease and Huntington's chorea. Under the terms of the agreement, <PERSON> Nova </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> would form separate partnerships to develop and market the painkillers and the central nervous system products. As part of the latter agreement, <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> would make an immediate cash payment of $ 25 million to <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> in return for 2.7 million newly issued common shares and warrants to purchase 775,000 shares of <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> at $ 9.28 a share. <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> has also agreed to purchase by December 1991 $ 24 million worth of Nova common stock and warrants to purchase an undisclosed number of shares at 15 percent above market price at the time of the purchase. The partnership, which is to be 60 percent owned by <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION>, would receive the right to license SmithKline's psychiatric drugs, including Thorazine and Stelazine _ which currently account for about $ 40 million in annual revenues _ once the first central nervous system product was marketed. The analgesics partnership calls for <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> to pay an initial $ 1 million and assume $ 21.5 million of debt primarily to commercialize the painkiller. <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> would manufacture it and obtain exclusive worldwide marketing rights, while <PERSON> Nova </PERSON> would retain a 50 percent share of control over that partnership and half the profits obtained from product sales. `` We fully expect to take a leadership role in the evolving field of neurobiology,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wendt </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said in a prepared statement. `` Nova's exciting research projects, together with our drug development and marketing capability, makes a powerful combination.''
