 The British government is considering selling off British Rail, the national railroad system, the Economist magazine reported in its latest issue. The plan is being worked on by a policy unit within Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s office, the magazine said in its May 21 issue, which was made available Friday. Spokesmen for the prime minister, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> said Friday they were unaware of any plans for the privatization of the railway. A report in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Evening </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>, however, said the prime minister's office confirmed that a study of the state company's privatization is in progress but stressed that it was at an early stage The Economist said three options are being explored. The first is selling the entire network as a going concern. But that would be made difficult by <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION>'s current troubled financial state, which requires government subsidies for operation. A second option calls for splitting <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> into regional companies. The magazine said this option is under study by <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourne </PERSON>, a special adviser in the prime minister's policy unit. <PERSON> Bourne </PERSON> declined to answer questions about the reports. The third option would be to form a `` track authority'' which would put operation of British Rail's track and signaling hardware up for private bidding, the magazine said. The Economist said plans for a split-up of British Rail into regional companies are also being studied by the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, a private think tank, which will publish its conclusions next month. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government has sold off billions of pounds worth of state assets, including <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the phone company, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, since she came into power in 1979. It currently is in the process of preparing the sale of the electicity industry of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>.
