<FIRST>u f AM-Seabrook Bjt   05-20 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook, Bjt,0907</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Years Later, PSNH Still Faces Nuclear Hurdles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty years after <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> announced it would build it own atomic reactor, the ill-fated <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> project has become a symbol for the problems that extinguished many of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s grandest hopes for nuclear power. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is the first major public power company to seek refuge from its creditors in bankruptcy court, and there remains no assurance that <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, its pricetag now at $ 5.4 billion and rising $ 50 million a month, ever will clear evacuation-planning hurdles and generate electricity. Spokesman <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashooh </PERSON> conceded this week that, with the benefit of hindsight, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> would have followed a different course if the decision to build were being made again. `` But that's irrelevant,'' <PERSON> Ashooh </PERSON> said. `` The bigger question is, how can we have a regulatory system that after 20 years can not make a decision on a major power project?'' <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> narrowly averted bankruptcy in 1984, completing a $ 425 million bond sale that was the largest financing in utility industry history. But nuclear disasters _ first at <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s Three Mile Island in 1979 and then at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1986 _ dealt <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> a devastating blow <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, now the likely 1988 Democratic presidential nominee, cited Chernobyl when he decided to oppose evacuation planning for <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities near <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has since become a key obstacle, though <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>'s evacuation plans also still lack final approval. The environment surrounding nuclear power in May 1968 and <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s early experiences with it gave little clue of the troubles that lay ahead. A byproduct of research that produced the atomic bomb during World War II, nuclear power in the 1940s and 1950s was seen by many as `` the key to the world's future,'' <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Flavin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Worldwatch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> wrote in his 1983 report `` Nuclear Power: The Market Test.'' `` It would supply infinite amounts of energy indefinitely and remove many of the constraints under which humanity had struggled for millennia,'' <PERSON> Flavin </PERSON> wrote. Another early claim by nuclear proponents was that it would provide energy too cheap to meter. Energy from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s first nuclear plant, <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rowe </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rowe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, was n't too cheap to meter. But it was only pennies per kilowatt-hour, cheaper than other alternatives at the time. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> owned 7 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rowe </ORGANIZATION>, which cost $ 44 million to build and began operation in 1960 as one of a half-dozen prototype reactors nationwide funded by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. By 1968, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> also had investments in other nuclear plants operating or under construction _ <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>. After conducting studies that projected continued strong growth in energy demand, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decided to join dozens of other utilities that were jumping on the nuclear bandwagon. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s largest power company announced on May 20, 1968, that it would build an 860-megawatt reactor on the <LOCATION> Piscataqua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Newington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> was to own 50 percent of the plant, with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illuminating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> to pick up most of the rest of the tab. The plant was to cost $ 150 million and be operating commercially by the fall of 1974, company Chairman <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiller </PERSON> announced. But the federal government squelched the original plan, saying the <LOCATION> Newington </LOCATION> location was too close to <ORGANIZATION> Pease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> chose an alternate site on marshland at <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> shelved the plans in 1969 after problems arose in financing the plant. Later, utility studies showed a need for a big new power plant, and the company revived its nuclear plans on Feb. 1, 1972. The plans were subsequently revised to include two 1,150-megawatt reactors, the first to be operating commercially in 1979, the second in 1981. The total cost was estimated at $ 850 million. Although the oil crisis of 1973 heightened awareness about energy, <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> began running into problems that earlier nuclear plants had not faced. <PERSON> Ashooh </PERSON> drew a comparison between <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Maine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wiscasset </LOCATION>, an 826-megawatt reactor that began operating in 1972 at a construction cost of $ 239 million. `` They went through their environmental -LRB- impact -RRB- hearings in an afternoon,'' <PERSON> Ashooh </PERSON> said. `` It took <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> several years.'' Controversy over <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s cooling-water system was n't finally settled until August 1978, causing years of delays and adding hundreds of millions of dollars to the plant's cost. By then, <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> also had become the target of highly visible opposition. Civil disobedience actions began at the plant site in 1976, months before groundbreaking, and a May 1977 protest that ended with 1,414 arrests _ the largest at any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear plant at that time _ made <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> the focus of the nation's anti-nuclear movement. As further delays kept boosting the project's pricetag, interest rates skyrocketed in the late 1970s, and <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s financial health deteriorated. In the aftermath of the partial meltdown at <LOCATION> Three </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> enacted rules that now represent the final major obstacle to a commercial license for <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>, requiring approved evacuation plans for a 10-mile zone around all nuclear power plants. Also in the spring of 1979, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallen </PERSON> signed a law barring utilities from charging ratepayers for power plants before they operate.
