<HEAD>Dollar Rises In Quiet European Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose in lackluster European trading Friday. Gold prices fell. Dealers said trading was extremely thin and quiet, partly because many traders on the Continent went home early before a three-day weekend. `` You could hear a pin drop in the trading room today,'' said one dealer at a British merchant bank. The dollar's slight gains were due to a flurry of buying in the morning after <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, the speaker of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s parliament, reiterated that his country was at war with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and called for an arms buildup. The dollar jumped up on the report. But then it barely moved for several hours until it edged back late in the day, dealers said. One dealer said market players did not take the report seriously but that it gave them something to do. The dollar was not affected by news that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer price index rose 0.4 percent in April because the rise was in line with expectations, dealers said. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. The pound fell to $ 1.8615 from $ 1.8665 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose fractionally to a closing 124.82 yen from 124.80 yen late Thursday. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 124.85 yen. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday, included: 1.7030 West German marks, up from 1.6990; 1.4195 Swiss francs, up from 1.4155; 5.7560 French francs, up from 5.7542; 1.9070 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9042; 1,263.50 Italian lire, up from 1,262.00; and 1.2420 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2442. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 45 cents a troy ounce to close at a bid $ 458.01 an ounce. Later gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 455.20 a troy ounce from late Thursday's $ 456.90. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 455.50 a troy ounce compared with $ 458.00 late Thursday. Silver bullion prices fell on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.64 a troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's $ 6.72 an ounce.
