<HEAD>Contracts Awarded For Developing New High-Speed Computer Chip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> selected four contractor teams Friday to develop a new type of high-speed, gallium arsenide computer chip. The three-year contracts, ranging in value from $ 49 million to about $ 69 million, call for each team to design, fabricate, package and test the same type of computer chip. Each team, however, is pursuing development of the chip with an eye toward its use in different weapons or communications systems, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. The chips `` are expected to be of great value for radar, electronic warfare, communications and smart munitions systems,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. It said the four contracts were awarded by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Projects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> DARPA </ORGANIZATION>, under a program known as MIMIC _ Microwave-Millimeter-Wave Monolithic Integrated Circuits. The four contractor teams are led by the <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The Martin-Marietta-ITT team includes four other partners and received a contract totaling $ 49.3 million. The <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> team includes three other partners and received a contract worth $ 57.5 million. The <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon-Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> team includes eight other partners and received a contract totaling $ 68.6 million. And the Hughes-GE team includes seven other partners and received a contract worth $ 50 million.
