<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks crawled to a mixed finish Friday in the lightest trading of the year, capping a loss-riddled week in which investor apathy and concern over higher interest rates dominated the market. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks spent part of the day barely ahead but weakened by late afternoon and finished with a 6.13 point loss to 1,952.59, bringing its decline for the week to 37.95. Broader market indices were mixed. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 120.6 million shares vs. 165.16 million the previous session. It was the most lethargic pace since a 111.58 million-share day Dec. 29. Without the inflating influence of dividend-capture trading in selected stocks, the volume would have been substantially lighter. `` It's just a continuation of complete lack of interest by the public,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Muldowney </PERSON>, head of equity trading at the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stringfellow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The government reported that consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in April. Although that level was widely anticipated by economists and traders, it substantiated some anxiety about inflation that haunted the market all week. This concern pushed yields on the key 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond to the 9.34 percent Friday, the highest of the year, making bonds an increasingly attractive and less risky alternative to stocks. `` The market has said something loud and clear: I'm going to attach myself to the tail of the bond market,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Shobin </PERSON>, a vice president and market analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Shobin </PERSON> said he saw the potential for a stock rally, arguing that fears over inflation are highly exaggerated and that any further substantial rise in interest rates is unlikely. `` I think the market has very little vulnerability here,'' <PERSON> Shobin </PERSON> said. `` The level of fear is very high right now, but fear is very fashionable. The market rarely rewards what the Street considers fashionable.'' Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3-to-2 in nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 841 issues up, 605 down and 514 unchanged. Among the most prominent <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> issues, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 ~ to 45 | on reports that the company was considering a restructuring plan that would reduce the 14.8 percent stake of its largest shareholder, takeover strategist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> Other notable blue chips included <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, up 1 -LCB- to 50 -LCB-; <ORGANIZATION> DuPont </ORGANIZATION>, down -RCB- to 80 -LCB-; <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, down 1 to 109 -LCB-; <PERSON> Merck </PERSON>, down 1 -RRB- to 149; and <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION>, up -LCB- to 18 | Interest-sensitive stocks such as banks and utilities were widely higher, suggesting that concern over higher interest rates may be peaking. <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> rose -RCB- to 26 |, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> rose -LRB- to 23 -RCB-, Manufacturers Hanover rose -RRB- to 26 -RRB-, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T rose -LRB- to 26 -RCB- and <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> rose -LCB- to 52 Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 142.40 million shares. The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of 5,000 <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, American and OTC issues, rose by $ 3.622 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> index rose 0.29 to 143.30. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 0.45 to 293.42, and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index also rose 0.45 to 253.02. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index fell 0.05 to 291.84. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market closed at 366.03, down 0.22.
