<HEAD>Sugarman Proposes Splitting Media General</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: grafs 10-15 new to UPDATE with Media General comment on vote
and edit, picks up 16th graf pvs: Sugarman criticized ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investor <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, apparently conceding that his $ 1.8 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has stalled, on Friday suggested splitting the communications firm into two or more parts. Speaking at the company's annual shareholders meeting, <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> also played down the bitter proxy fight he has waged with Media General Chairman <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennant </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> over the election of directors to the company's board. `` The questions that I have are not based on personalities,'' <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> said. `` It's time to get down to business ... Let's meet together. Let's talk together.'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, whose family owns 71 percent of Media General's powerful Class B shares, presided at the meeting but did not respond to <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s offer to negotiate. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> has said the family's stake in the company is not for sale. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, who controls about 10 percent of the company's Class A shares, initially offered $ 61.50 a share, but later boosted his bid to $ 70 a share. Subsequently, he and two allies have challenged three directors seeking re-election to <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION>'s nine-member board. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> told the stockholders that his slate would be fair to the <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION> and would seek to split the company's assets in a way that preserved the family's publishing concerns. `` My interest is not in taking the newspapers away'' from the <ORGANIZATION> Bryans </ORGANIZATION>, he said. In addition to the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News Leader, the <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and other daily and weekly newspapers, <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> owns several television stations and cable television operations. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, meanwhile, received a lengthy ovation from the crowd of about 400 shareholders when he read his own name for re-election to the board. Because of delays in counting proxy votes, the tally on the election of directors will not be released until May 27. But Media General President and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, said `` based on the proxies that we have received, we believe the incumbent ... directors have defeated <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> and his dissident slate.'' <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>, however, said after the two-hour meeting that he believed the vote was nearly even. `` I think you'll find I was not the only shareholder who voted for our slate,'' he said. But several shareholders said <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s proposal to split the company indicated some doubt about his chances. Still, <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> said his $ 70-per-share bid still stands. Media General closed Thursday at $ 42.62 -LCB- a share. `` Look at the disparity in those numbers,'' he said. The stock dropped $ 1.12 -LCB- a share Friday to close at $ 41.37 -LCB- on the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> criticized the two-tier stock arrangement and said he was seeking congressional action to eliminate such structures. Last month a federal district court in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> rejected <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON>'s challenge to the system Like several media companies including the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> has two classes of stock to keep control of the company in the hands of a few. While there are fewer Class B shares outstanding, those shares are more powerful than the Class A shares. Under Media General's arrangement, the <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> family controls the election of a majority of the board through its Class-B shares. <PERSON> Sugarman </PERSON> is chairman of the California-based <ORGANIZATION> Barris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, which produces `` The Dating Game'' and other popular television game shows and the South Carolina-based <ORGANIZATION> Giant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a cement company.
