<HEAD>Platinum Surges As Inflation Signals Strengthen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Platinum futures prices jumped more than $ 11 a troy ounce Friday, leading other precious metals higher as key indicators reinforced ideas that inflation is worsening, analysts said. On other markets, most livestock and meat futures gained; the pork markets received some startling news about supplies; grains and soybeans advanced; energy futures were mixed; and stock index futures retreated. A combination of inflationary signals and indications of economic growth have made platinum the leader of the precious-metals complex because platinum is used as both an industrial metal and a hedge against inflation, analysts said. Friday's government report showing a 0.4 percent increase in consumer prices in April supported the metals rally on Friday. But the real boost came late in the day when a sudden surge in soybean and grain futures prices propelled the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s price index of 21 commodities up sharply With Friday's 1.31-point gain, the CRB index for May delivery ended the week at 246.11, up 6.81 points from the previous Friday's close on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> `` That's really a fantastic move,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON>, metals analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` All these things _ commodity prices, strength of the economy _ they're all feeding into why the metals are beginning to move. Platinum settled $ 11.10 to $ 11.20 higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with the contract for delivery in July at $ 568.60 a troy ounce. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold was 50 cents to 70 cents higher with June at $ 458.70 a troy ounce; silver was 7.5 cents to 7.9 cents higher with May at $ 6.69 a troy ounce. Livestock and meat futures finished mostly higher in light, pre-weekend trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. But a government cold-storage report released after the close prompted predictions that pork futures would open lower on Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the number of hams in cold storage nearly doubled during April to 51.6 million pounds. That compares with 24 million pounds on April 1 and 11.3 million pounds on May 1, 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said the total amount of pork in cold storage was up 82 percent from last year, including 102.5 million pounds of frozen pork bellies, the third-largest May 1 total ever, said <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, an analysts in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The large stocks of frozen pork wo n't have an immediate impact on futures prices but will begin exerting heavy price pressure in July, when demand for pork products typically outstrips the supply of fresh meat, <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said. Live cattle settled .40 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at 73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25 cent higher with May at 80.90 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .35 cent higher with June at 53.87 cents a po