<HEAD>Judge Grants Limited Extension in Bankruptcy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday granted <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> at least four extra months to come up with a reorganization plan, and may grant another two months after that. After a seven-hour hearing, Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> said he doubted he would grant the utility the eight months it had requested. But he said the utility was entitled at least to a four-month extension because `` the first 120 days have been used for organization in a rather unique case. `` Realistically, -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is only now in a position they would be in the first few weeks of a normal case,'' <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> said. Federal bankruptcy law gives a debtor the exclusive right to propose a reorganization plan for 120 days after it files for protection from creditors. The exclusivity period for <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> _ the state's largest electric utility and main owner of the stalled <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power plant _ ends May 27. It had asked for an eight-month extension, citing the complexity and uniqueness of the case. <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> said he would consider lengthening the extension later if he was assured that parties involved in the reorganization had adequate access to information needed to develop and negotiate a plan. <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> said he either would grant a four-month extension with a hearing in September to consider more time, or would grant a six-month extension with a hearing in September to be certain that necessary information is being made available to all involved. Several lawyers representing other parties to the bankruptcy had proposed shorter extension periods. But <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> said he was not convinced that it yet was appropriate to open up the reorganization process to other proposals, although he noted that `` one way to make things move is to make them concrete, put them on the table.'' <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> sought bankruptcy protection because of financial problems stemming from its 36 percent share of the $ 5.4 billion Seabrook plant. It blames its woes largely on political opposition to <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> and a state law barring the company from charging customers for the plant until it operates commercially, which had forced the company to borrow heavily.
